# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adulis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adulis/adulis] Archeological excavations conducted at Adulis unearthed the existence of a late prehistoric settlement beneath the town, dating from the mid-2nd to early 1st millennium BCE.
[src:adulis/adulis] Adulis may correspond to *Wddt*, a region recorded in the geographical lists of Egypt’s 18th dynasty (ca.
[src:adulis/adulis] Several theories have been proposed regarding the origin of the name **Adulis**.
[src:adulis/adulis] One theory derives the name from the Saho term *ado lay*, meaning "white water" or "clear water".
[src:adulis/adulis] The term is composed of *ado* ("white") and *lay* ("water") and is used by Saho speakers to describe settlements associated with reliable sources of clean water.
[src:adulis/adulis] Pliny the Elder is the earliest European writer to mention Adulis (N.H.
[src:adulis/adulis] He misunderstood the name of the place, thinking the toponym meant that it had been founded by escaped Egyptian slaves.
[src:adulis/adulis] Pliny further stated that it was the 'principal mart for the Troglodytae and the people of Aethiopia'.
[src:adulis/adulis] Adulis is also mentioned in the *Periplus of the Erythraean Sea*, a guide of the Red Sea and the Indian Ocean.
[src:adulis/adulis] The latter guide describes the settlement as an emporium for the ivory, hides, slaves and other exports of the interior.
[src:adulis/adulis] Roman merchants used the port in the second and third century AD.
[src:adulis/adulis] It appears that the city was located some distance from its actual port—approximately 20 stades away—which sources refer to as "the harbour of the ʿAdulītā".
[src:adulis/adulis] Further evidence of this distinction can be seen in the fact that the ʿAdulītā are sometimes mentioned separately from the Aksumites.
[src:adulis/adulis] Epiphanius, when listing the nine kingdoms of the "Indians", distinguishes between the Aksumites and the "ʿAdulītā".
[src:adulis/adulis] In reality, the principal harbour where ships moored may have been located at a site known as Gabaza.
[src:adulis/adulis] The settlement is mentioned in the *Martyrdom of Arethas* (also known as the *Martyrs of Najran*), where it appears as a harbour associated with Adulis.
[src:adulis/adulis] Archaeologists have recently proposed that Gabaza was situated in the Galala Hills, south of Adulis, where the remains of two ancient circular watchtowers have been identified.
[src:adulis/adulis] A fourth century work traditionally ascribed to the writer Palladius of Galatia, relates the journey of an anonymous Egyptian lawyer (*scholasticus*) to India in order to investigate Brahmin philosophy.
[src:adulis/adulis] He was accompanied part of the way by one Moise or Moses, the Bishop of Adulis.
[src:adulis/adulis] The existence of the See of Adulis is also confirmed by the Notitiae Episcopatuum.
[src:adulis/adulis] Yuri Kobishchanov detailed a number of raids Aksumites made on the Arabian coast (the latest being in 702, when the port of Jeddah was occupied), and argued that Adulis was later destroyed by the Muslims, which brought to an end Axum's naval power and contributed to the Aksumite Kingdom's isolation.
[src:adulis/adulis] It has traditionally been claimed that the town was destroyed in 640 AD by an Arab expedition; however, the evidence remains inconclusive.
[src:adulis/adulis] While excavations have revealed traces of fire, historical records indicate that the Arab expedition was ultimately considered a failure.
[src:adulis/adulis] Muslim writers occasionally mention the nearby Dahlak Archipelago as places of exile.
[src:adulis/adulis] In any case, the naval power of Axum waned and the port of Adulis was abandoned sometime around the 8th century AD.
[src:adulis/adulis] Adulis was one of the first Axumite sites to undergo excavation, when a French mission to Eritrea under Vignaud and Petit performed an initial survey in 1840, and prepared a map which marked the location of three structures they believed were temples.
[src:adulis/adulis] In 1868, workers attached to Napier's campaign against Tewodros II visited Adulis and exposed several buildings, including the foundations of a Byzantine-like church.
[src:adulis/adulis] The first scientific excavations at Adulis were undertaken in 1906, under the supervision of Richard Sundström.
[src:adulis/adulis] Sundström worked in the northern sector of the site, exposing a large structure, which he dubbed the "palace of Adulis", as well as recovering some examples of Axumite coinage.
[src:adulis/adulis] The Italian Roberto Paribeni excavated in Adulis the following year, discovering many structures similar to what Sundström had found earlier, as well as a number of ordinary dwellings.
[src:adulis/adulis] He found a lot of pottery: even wine amphorae imported from the area of modern Aqaba were found here during the decades of existence of the colony of Italian Eritrea.
[src:adulis/adulis] These types now called Ayla-Axum Amphoras have since been found at other sites in Eritrea including on Black Assarca Island.
[src:adulis/adulis] Over 50 years passed until the next series of excavations, when in 1961 and 1962 the Ethiopian Institute of Archeology sponsored an expedition led by Francis Anfray.
[src:adulis/adulis] This excavation not only recovered materials showing a strong affinities with the late Axumite kingdom, but a destruction layer.
[src:adulis/adulis] This in turn prompted Kobishchanov to later argue that Adulis had been destroyed by an Arab raid in the mid-7th century, a view that has since been partially rejected.
[src:adulis/adulis] A pair of fragments of glass vessels were found in the lowest layers at Adulis, which are similar to specimens from the 18th Dynasty of Egypt.
[src:adulis/adulis] One very specialised imported vessel discovered at the site was a Menas flask.
[src:adulis/adulis] It was stamped with a design showing the Egyptian St.
[src:adulis/adulis] Such vessels are supposed to have held water from a spring near the saint's tomb in Egypt (Paribeni 1907: 538, fig.
[src:adulis/adulis] 54), and this particular one may have been brought to Adulis by a pilgrim.
[src:adulis/adulis] Since Eritrean Independence, the National Museum of Eritrea has petitioned the Government of Ethiopia to return artifacts of these excavations.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Ancient **Aethiopia** (Greek: Αἰθιοπία, romanized: *Aithiopía*) first appears as a geographical term in classical documents in reference to the skin color of the inhabitants of the upper Nile in Sudan, areas south of the Sahara, and less often to certain parts of Asia.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Its earliest mention is in the works of Homer: twice in the *Iliad*, and three times in the *Odyssey*.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] The Greek historian Herodotus uses the appellation to refer to regions south of Egypt when describing "Aethiopians," most commonly Nubians.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Despite this, the Byzantine Greeks also started to call the Aksumites Ethiopians after Negus Ezana, who conquered Meroë in 330AD and took on the title of "king of Ethiopia" from the Nubians.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Greco-Roman sources also report the existence of 'White Aethiopians' in Africa.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] By the modern period, the term Aethiopian Sea was used to refer to the southern Atlantic Ocean, particularly the area adjacent to West Africa.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Though near universally used to invoke the "Aethiopia of Africa" ("African Aethiopia"), there was another region sometimes called Asiatic Aethiopia, located somewhere in 'the East'.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Unlike the earlier Greek writers who distinguished Aethiopians (Nubians) from other types of Africans, Claudius Ptolemy (90–168 AD), a Roman citizen of Greek culture who lived in Alexandria, used "Aethiopia" as a generic term for Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Pseudo-Jerome in the 4th century or later referred to the region of Colchis as the "Other Aethiopia" (*altera Aethiopia*), or, in the Greek translation of Pseudo-Sophronius, the "Second Aethiopia" (ἐν τῇ δευτέρᾳ Αἰθιοπίᾳ).
[src:adulis/aethiopia] The Greek name *Aithiopia* (Αἰθιοπία, from Αἰθίοψ, *Aithíops*) is a compound derived of two Greek words: αἴθω, *aíthō*, 'I burn' + ὤψ, *ṓps*, 'face'.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] According to the Perseus Digital Library, this designation properly translates in noun form as *burnt-face* and in adjectival form as *red-brown*.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] As such, it was used as a vague term for darker skinned populations than the Greeks since the time of Homer.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] The term was applied to such peoples within the range of observation of the ancient geographers, primarily in what was then Nubia (in ancient Sudan).
[src:adulis/aethiopia] With the expansion of geographical knowledge, the exonym successively extended to certain other areas below the Sahara.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] In classical antiquity, the term *Africa* did not refer to any part of sub-Saharan Africa, but rather, in its widest sense, to Ancient Libya—what is now known as the Maghreb and the desert to the south.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] 8th century BC) is the first to mention "Aethiopians" (Αἰθίοπες, Αἰθιοπῆες), writing that they are to be found at the east and west extremities of the world, divided by the sea into "eastern" (at the sunrise) and "western" (at the sunset).
[src:adulis/aethiopia] In Book 1 of the *Iliad*, Thetis visits Olympus to meet Zeus, but the meeting is postponed, as Zeus and other gods are absent, visiting the land of the Aethiopians.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Meanwhile, in Book 1 of the *Odyssey*, Athena convinces Zeus to let Odysseus finally return home only because Poseidon is away in Aithiopia and unable to object.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] 8th century BC) speaks of Memnon as the "King of the Aethiopians." In *The Catalogues of Women*, he stated that the Egyptian king Epaphus was the progenitor of the Aethiopians and other dark-skinned tribes of Libya.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] The Assyrian king Esarhaddon when conquering Egypt and destroying the Kushite Empire states how he "deported all 'Aethiopians' from Egypt, leaving not one to pay homage to me".
[src:adulis/aethiopia] He was talking about the Nubian 25th Dynasty rather than people from modern Ethiopia.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] In 515 BC, Scylax of Caryanda, on orders from Darius I of the Achaemenid Empire, sailed along the Indus River, Indian Ocean, and Red Sea, circumnavigating the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] He mentioned "Aethiopians", though his writings on them have not survived.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] 500 BC) is also said to have written a book about 'Aethiopia,' but his writing is now known only through quotations from later authors.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] He stated that 'Aethiopia' was located to the east of the Nile, as far as the Red Sea and Indian Ocean.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] He is also quoted as relating a myth in which the Skiapods ('Shade feet'), whose feet were supposedly large enough to serve as shade, lived there.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] 440 BC), Herodotus presents some of the most ancient and detailed information about "Aethiopia".
[src:adulis/aethiopia] He relates that he personally traveled up the Nile to the border of Egypt as far as Elephantine (modern Aswan).
[src:adulis/aethiopia] In his view, "Aethiopia" is all of the inhabited land found to the south of Egypt, beginning at Elephantine.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] He describes a capital at Meroë, adding that the only deities worshipped there were Zeus (Amun) and Dionysus (Osiris).
[src:adulis/aethiopia] He relates that in the reign of Pharaoh Psamtik I (c.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] 650 BCE), many Egyptian soldiers deserted their country and settled amidst the Aethiopians.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Herodotus remarked on shared cultural practices between the Egyptians and Ethiopians, also stating that out of "three hundred and thirty kings" of Egypt, there had been 18 Ethiopian kings, one native Egyptian queen, and the rest had been Egyptian men.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Herodotus tells us that king Cambyses II (c.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] 570 BC) of the Achaemenid Empire sent spies to the Aethiopians "who dwelt in that part of Libya (Africa) which borders upon the southern sea." They found a strong and healthy people.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Although Cambyses then campaigned toward their country, by not preparing enough provisions for the long march, his army completely failed and returned quickly.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] In Book 3, Herodotus defines "Aethiopia" as the farthest region of "Libya" (i.e.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Herodotus also wrote that the Ammonians of Siwa Oasis are "colonists from Egypt and Aethiopia and speak a language compounded of the tongues of both countries".
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Herodotus also refers to "the Aethiopians of Asia" (or "Ethiopians of the East"), who are said to be straight-haired, whereas the Aethiopians from Libya (Africa) have "the woolliest hair of all men".
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Herodotus wrote with regard to the inhabitants of Libya (the Greek name for Africa): "One thing I can add about this far country [Libya]: so far as one knows, it is inhabited by four races, and four only, of which two are indigenous and two not.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] According to Herodotus the Macrobians dwelt geographically along the sea south of Libya on the Atlantic.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] This Libya was far south of the Pillars of Hercules and Atlas Mountains along the Atlantic coast, while the northern Libyan sea coast was the Mediterranean Sea that stretched from Egypt to Morocco in an east to west direction.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Concerning the southern sea, Herodotus places the Persians east of the southern sea in Asia, the Arabians & East Africans south of the sea in Arabia and the Macrobians west of the southern Sea in Libya.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Herodotus also stated that the Macrobians were indigenous to southern Libya while the Libyans along the Mediterranean Sea were indigenous to northern Libya.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] According to his account, the Persian Emperor Cambyses II upon his conquest of Egypt (525 BC) sent ambassadors to Macrobia, bringing luxury gifts for its king to entice his submission.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Herodotus also mentions a silent trade of gold that took place between Carthaginians and natives south of Libya beyond the Pillars of Hercules; it was also this gold trade that motivated Cambyses, the King of Persia, to plan a land and sea expedition against both the Carthaginians and Macrobian.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Pliny in his natural histories places them west of Meroe, far west of Meroe beyond the deserts of Chad that is.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Cambyses, after being insulted by the tallest and long-lived (Macrobian) King of Ethiopia in the west, he eagerly wanted to conquer and subdue all people of Amun and destroy all temples of the God, but failed in his desperate attempt.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] 300 BC) listed Kushite (25th) dynasty, calling it the "Aethiopian dynasty," and Esarhaddon the early 7th century BC ruler of the Neo-Assyrian Empire describes deporting all "Aethiopians" from Egypt upon conquering Egypt from the Nubian Kushite Empire which formed the 25th Dynasty.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Moreover, when the Hebrew Bible was translated into Greek (c.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] 200 BC), the Hebrew appellation "Kush, Kushite" became in Greek "Aethiopia, Aethiopians", appearing as "Ethiopia, Ethiopians" in the English *King James Version*.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Agatharchides provides a relatively detailed description of the gold mining system of Aethiopia.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] His text was copied almost verbatim by virtually all subsequent ancient writers on the area, including Diodorus Siculus and Photius.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] He recounted this story that attributes the origins of Egyptian civilization to migrants from the south, which in this context corresponds to the Kingdom of Kush.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Achilles Tatius described the complexion of the Egyptian herdsmen near Alexandria as "dark-coloured (yet not absolutely black like an Indian but more like a bastard Ethiopian)".
[src:adulis/aethiopia] He also writes that the "Queen of the Ethiopians" bore the title Kandake, and avers (incorrectly) that the Ethiopians had conquered ancient Syria and the Mediterranean.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Following Strabo, the Greco-Roman historian Eusebius claims that the Ethiopians had emigrated into the Red Sea area from the Indus Valley and that there were no people in the region by that name prior to their arrival.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] The Greek travelogue from the 1st-century AD, known as the *Periplus of the Erythraean Sea*, initially describes the littoral, based on its author's intimate knowledge of the area.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] However, the *Periplus* does not mention any dark-skinned "Ethiopians" among the area's inhabitants.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] They only later appear in Ptolemy's *Geographia* in a region far south, around the "Bantu nucleus" of northern Mozambique.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] The terms King and Kingdom of Ethiopia would later be used by, among others, Amda Seyon I and Zara Yaqob.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Early in the history of Italian Eritrea the name "Nuova Etiopia" (New Ethiopia) was proposed.
[src:adulis/aethiopia] Also the Roman Christian Pseudo-Jerome and his translator Pseudo-Sophronius referred to Colchis as the "other Ethiopia" or "second Ethiopia".
[src:adulis/aethiopia] 245 AD) had written in his journeys and life of Apollonios of Tyana, he had at one point arrived at "the crossing point between Ethiopia and Egypt, which is called Kaminos", where at a marketplace the Ethiopians and Egyptians would trade and barter products.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The pinnacle of ancient Egyptian power was achieved during the New Kingdom, which extended its rule to much of Nubia and a considerable portion of the Levant.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] After this period, Egypt entered an era of slow decline.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Over the course of its history, it was invaded or conquered by a number of foreign civilizations, including the Hyksos, the Kushites, the Assyrians, the Persians, and the Greeks and then the Romans.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The end of ancient Egypt is variously defined as occurring with the end of the Late Period during the Wars of Alexander the Great in 332 BC or with the end of the Greek-ruled Ptolemaic Kingdom during the Roman conquest of Egypt in 30 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] In AD 642, the Arab conquest of Egypt brought an end to the region's millennium-long Greco-Roman period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The success of ancient Egyptian civilization came partly from its ability to adapt to the Nile's conditions for agriculture.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The predictable flooding of the Nile and controlled irrigation of its fertile valley produced surplus crops which supported a more dense population and thereby substantial social and cultural development.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Motivating and organizing these activities was a bureaucracy of elite scribes, religious leaders, and administrators under the control of the reigning pharaoh, who ensured the cooperation and unity of the Egyptian people in the context of an elaborate system of religious beliefs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Its art and architecture were widely copied and its antiquities were carried off to be studied, admired, or coveted in the far corners of the world.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Likewise, its monumental ruins inspired the imaginations of travelers and writers for millennia.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] A newfound European and Egyptian respect for antiquities and excavations that began in earnest in the early modern period has led to much scientific investigation of ancient Egypt and its society, as well as a greater appreciation of its cultural legacy.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Nile has been the lifeline of its region for much of human history.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The fertile floodplain of the Nile gave humans the opportunity to develop a settled agricultural economy and a more sophisticated, centralized society that became a cornerstone in the history of human civilization.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] In Predynastic and Early Dynastic times, the Egyptian climate was much less arid than it is today.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Large regions of Egypt were savanna and traversed by herds of grazing ungulates.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Foliage and fauna were far more prolific in all environs, and the Nile region supported large populations of waterfowl.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Hunting would have been common for Egyptians, and this is also the period when many animals were first domesticated.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] By about 5500 BC, small tribes living in the Nile valley had developed into a series of cultures demonstrating firm control of agriculture and animal husbandry, and identifiable by their pottery and personal items, such as combs, bracelets, and beads.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The largest of these early cultures in upper (Southern) Egypt was the Badarian culture, which probably originated in the Western Desert; it was known for its high-quality ceramics, stone tools, and its use of copper.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Badari was followed by the Naqada culture: the Naqada I (Amratian), the Naqada II (Gerzeh), and Naqada III (Semainean).
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] These brought a number of technological improvements.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] As early as the Naqada I Period, predynastic Egyptians imported obsidian from Ethiopia, used to shape blades and other objects from flakes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Mutual trade with the Levant was established during Naqada II (c.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] 3600–3350 BC); this period was also the beginning of trade with Mesopotamia, which continued into the early dynastic period and beyond.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Over a period of about 1,000 years, the Naqada culture developed from a few small farming communities into a powerful civilization whose leaders were in complete control of the people and resources of the Nile valley.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Establishing a power center at Nekhen, and later at Abydos, Naqada III leaders expanded their control of Egypt northwards along the Nile.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] They also traded with Nubia to the south, the oases of the western desert to the west, and the cultures of the eastern Mediterranean and Near East to the east.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] They also developed a ceramic glaze known as faience, which was used well into the Roman Period to decorate cups, amulets, and figurines.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] During the last predynastic phase, the Naqada culture began using written symbols that eventually were developed into a full system of hieroglyphs for writing the ancient Egyptian language.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Early Dynastic Period was approximately contemporary to the early Sumerian-Akkadian civilization of Mesopotamia and of ancient Elam.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The third-century BC Egyptian priest Manetho grouped the long line of kings from Menes to his own time into 30 dynasties, a system still used today.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] He began his official history with the king named "Meni" (or Menes in Greek), who was believed to have united the two kingdoms of Upper and Lower Egypt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The transition to a unified state happened more gradually than ancient Egyptian writers represented, and there is no contemporary record of Menes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Some scholars now believe, however, that the mythical Menes may have been the king Narmer, who is depicted wearing royal regalia on the ceremonial *Narmer Palette*, in a symbolic act of unification.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The increasing power and wealth of the kings during the early dynastic period was reflected in their elaborate mastaba tombs and mortuary cult structures at Abydos, which were used to celebrate the deified king after his death.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The strong institution of kingship developed by the kings served to legitimize state control over the land, labor, and resources that were essential to the survival and growth of ancient Egyptian civilization.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Major advances in architecture, art, and technology were made during the Old Kingdom, fueled by the increased agricultural productivity and resulting population growth, made possible by a well-developed central administration.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Some of ancient Egypt's crowning achievements, the Giza pyramids and Great Sphinx, were constructed during the Old Kingdom.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Under the direction of the vizier, state officials collected taxes, coordinated irrigation projects to improve crop yield, and drafted peasants to work on construction projects.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] With the rise of central administration in Egypt, a new class of educated scribes and officials emerged and were granted estates by the king as payment for their services.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Kings also made land grants to their mortuary cults and local temples, to ensure that these institutions had the resources to worship the king after his death.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Scholars believe that five centuries of these practices slowly eroded the economic vitality of Egypt, and that the economy could no longer afford to support a large centralized administration.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] As the power of the kings diminished, regional governors called nomarchs began to challenge the supremacy of the office of king.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] This, coupled with severe droughts between 2200 and 2150 BC, is believed to have caused the country to enter the 140-year period of famine and strife known as the First Intermediate Period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] After Egypt's central government collapsed at the end of the Old Kingdom, the administration could no longer support or stabilize the country's economy.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The ensuing food shortages and political disputes escalated into famines and small-scale civil wars.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Yet despite difficult problems, local leaders, owing no tribute to the king, used their new-found independence to establish a thriving culture in the provinces.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Once in control of their own resources, the provinces became economically richer—which was demonstrated by larger and better burials among all social classes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Free from their loyalties to the king, local rulers began competing with each other for territorial control and political power.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] By 2160 BC, rulers in Herakleopolis controlled Lower Egypt in the north, while a rival clan based in Thebes, the Intef family, took control of Upper Egypt in the south.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] As the Intefs grew in power and expanded their control northward, a clash between the two rival dynasties became inevitable.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Around 2055 BC the northern Theban forces under Nebhepetre Mentuhotep II finally defeated the Herakleopolitan rulers, reuniting the Two Lands.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] They inaugurated a period of economic and cultural renaissance known as the Middle Kingdom.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The kings of the Middle Kingdom restored the country's stability, which saw a resurgence of art and monumental building projects, and a new flourishing of literature.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Mentuhotep II and his Eleventh Dynasty successors ruled from Thebes, but the vizier Amenemhat I, upon assuming the kingship at the beginning of the Twelfth Dynasty around 1985 BC, shifted the kingdom's capital to the city of Itjtawy, located in Faiyum.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] From Itjtawy, the kings of the Twelfth Dynasty undertook a far-sighted land reclamation and irrigation scheme to increase agricultural output in the region.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Moreover, the military reconquered territory in Nubia that was rich in quarries and gold mines, while laborers built a defensive structure in the Eastern Delta, called the "Walls of the Ruler", to defend against foreign attack.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] With the kings having secured the country militarily and politically and with vast agricultural and mineral wealth at their disposal, the nation's population, arts, and religion flourished.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Middle Kingdom displayed an increase in expressions of personal piety toward the gods.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Middle Kingdom literature featured sophisticated themes and characters written in a confident, eloquent style.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The relief and portrait sculpture of the period captured subtle, individual details that reached new heights of technical sophistication.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Around 1785 BC, as the power of the Middle Kingdom kings weakened, a Western Asian people called the Hyksos, who had already settled in the Delta, seized control of Egypt and established their capital at Avaris, forcing the former central government to retreat to Thebes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The king was treated as a vassal and expected to pay tribute.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Hyksos ('foreign rulers') retained Egyptian models of government and identified as kings, thereby integrating Egyptian elements into their culture.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] After retreating south, the native Theban kings found themselves trapped between the Canaanite Hyksos ruling the north and the Hyksos' Nubian allies, the Kushites, to the south.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] After years of vassalage, Thebes gathered enough strength to challenge the Hyksos in a conflict that lasted more than 30 years, until 1555 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Ahmose I waged a series of campaigns that permanently eradicated the Hyksos' presence in Egypt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] He is considered the founder of the Eighteenth Dynasty, and the military became a central priority for his successors, who sought to expand Egypt's borders and attempted to gain mastery of the Near East.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The New Kingdom pharaohs established a period of unprecedented prosperity by securing their borders and strengthening diplomatic ties with their neighbours, including the Mitanni Empire, Assyria, and Canaan.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Military campaigns waged under Thutmose I and his grandson Thutmose III extended the influence of the pharaohs to the largest empire Egypt had ever seen.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Between their reigns, Hatshepsut, a queen who established herself as pharaoh, launched many building projects, including the restoration of temples damaged by the Hyksos, and sent trading expeditions to Punt and the Sinai.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] When Tuthmosis III died in 1425 BC, Egypt had an empire extending from Niya in north west Syria to the Fourth Cataract of the Nile in Nubia, cementing loyalties and opening access to critical imports such as bronze and wood.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The New Kingdom pharaohs began a large-scale building campaign to promote the god Amun, whose growing cult was based in Karnak.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] They also constructed monuments to glorify their own achievements, both real and imagined.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Karnak temple is the largest Egyptian temple ever built.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Around 1350 BC, the stability of the New Kingdom was threatened when Amenhotep IV ascended the throne and instituted a series of radical and chaotic reforms.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Changing his name to Akhenaten, he touted the previously obscure sun deity Aten as the supreme deity, suppressed the worship of most other deities, and moved the capital to the new city of Akhetaten (modern-day Amarna).
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] He was devoted to his new religion and artistic style.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] After his death, the cult of the Aten was quickly abandoned and the traditional religious order restored.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The subsequent pharaohs, Tutankhamun, Ay, and Horemheb, worked to erase all mention of Akhenaten's heresy, now known as the Amarna Period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Around 1279 BC, Ramesses II, also known as Ramesses the Great, ascended the throne, and went on to build more temples, erect more statues and obelisks, and sire more children than any other pharaoh in history.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] A bold military leader, Ramesses II led his army against the Hittites in the Battle of Kadesh (in modern Syria) and, after fighting to a stalemate, finally agreed to the first recorded peace treaty, around 1258 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Egypt's wealth, however, made it a tempting target for invasion, particularly by the Libyan Berbers to the west, and the Sea Peoples, a conjectured confederation of seafarers from the Aegean Sea.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Initially, the military was able to repel these invasions, but Egypt eventually lost control of its remaining territories in southern Canaan, much of it falling to the Assyrians.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The effects of external threats were exacerbated by internal problems such as corruption, tomb robbery, and civil unrest.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] After regaining their power, the high priests at the temple of Amun in Thebes accumulated vast tracts of land and wealth, and their expanded power splintered the country during the Third Intermediate Period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Following the death of Ramesses XI in 1078 BC, Smendes assumed authority over the northern part of Egypt, ruling from the city of Tanis.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The south was effectively controlled by the High Priests of Amun at Thebes, who recognized Smendes in name only.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] During this time, Libyans had been settling in the western delta, and chieftains of these settlers began increasing their autonomy.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Libyan princes took control of the delta under Shoshenq I in 945 BC, founding the so-called Libyan or Bubastite dynasty that would rule for some 200 years.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Shoshenq also gained control of southern Egypt by placing his family members in important priestly positions.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Libyan control began to erode as a rival dynasty in the delta arose in Leontopolis, and Kushites threatened from the south.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Around 727 BC the Kushite king Piye invaded northward, seizing control of Thebes and eventually the Delta, which established the 25th Dynasty.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] During the 25th Dynasty, Pharaoh Taharqa created an empire nearly as large as the New Kingdom's.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Twenty-fifth Dynasty pharaohs built, or restored, temples and monuments throughout the Nile valley, including at Memphis, Karnak, Kawa, and Jebel Barkal.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] During this period, the Nile valley saw the first widespread construction of pyramids (many in modern Sudan) since the Middle Kingdom.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Egypt's far-reaching prestige declined considerably toward the end of the Third Intermediate Period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Its foreign allies had fallen into the Assyrian sphere of influence, and by 700 BC war between the two states became inevitable.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Between 671 and 667 BC the Assyrians began the Assyrian conquest of Egypt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The reigns of both Taharqa and his successor, Tanutamun, were filled with frequent conflict with the Assyrians.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Ultimately, the Assyrians pushed the Kushites back into Nubia, occupied Memphis, and sacked the temples of Thebes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Assyrians left control of Egypt to a series of vassals who became known as the Saite kings of the Twenty-Sixth Dynasty.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] By 653 BC, the Saite king Psamtik I was able to oust the Assyrians with the help of Greek mercenaries, who were recruited to form Egypt's first navy.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Greek influence expanded greatly as the city-state of Naucratis became the home of Greeks in the Nile Delta.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Saite kings based in the new capital of Sais witnessed a brief but spirited resurgence in the economy and culture, but in 525 BC, the Persian Empire, led by Cambyses II, began its conquest of Egypt, eventually defeating the pharaoh Psamtik III at the Battle of Pelusium.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Cambyses II then assumed the formal title of pharaoh, but ruled Egypt from Iran, leaving Egypt under the control of a satrap.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] A few revolts against the Persians marked the 5th century BC, but Egypt was unable to overthrow the Persians until the end of the century.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Following its annexation by Persia, Egypt was joined with Cyprus and Phoenicia in the sixth satrapy of the Achaemenid Persian Empire.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] This first period of Persian rule over Egypt, also known as the Twenty-Seventh Dynasty, ended in 402 BC, when Egypt regained independence under a series of native dynasties.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The last of these dynasties, the Thirtieth, proved to be the last native royal house of ancient Egypt, ending with the kingship of Nectanebo II.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] A brief restoration of Persian rule, sometimes known as the Thirty-First Dynasty, began in 343 BC, but shortly after, in 332 BC, the Persian ruler Mazaces handed Egypt over to Alexander the Great without a fight.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] In 332 BC, Alexander the Great conquered Egypt with little resistance from the Persians and was welcomed by the Egyptians as a deliverer.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The administration established by Alexander's successors, the Macedonian Ptolemaic Kingdom, was based on an Egyptian model and based in the new capital city of Alexandria.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The city showcased the power and prestige of Hellenistic rule, and became a centre of learning and culture that included the famous Library of Alexandria and the Mouseion.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Lighthouse of Alexandria lit the way for the many ships that kept trade flowing through the city—as the Ptolemies made commerce and revenue-generating enterprises, such as papyrus manufacturing, their top priority.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Hellenistic culture did not supplant native Egyptian culture, as the Ptolemies supported time-honored traditions in an effort to secure the loyalty of the populace.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] They built new temples in Egyptian style, supported traditional cults, and portrayed themselves as pharaohs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Some traditions merged, as Greek and Egyptian gods were syncretized into composite deities, such as Serapis, and classical Greek forms of sculpture influenced traditional Egyptian motifs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Despite their efforts to appease the Egyptians, the Ptolemies were challenged by native rebellion, bitter family rivalries, and frequent mob violence in Alexandria.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] In addition, as Rome relied more heavily on imports of grain from Egypt, the Romans took great interest in the political situation in the country.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Continued Egyptian revolts, ambitious politicians, and powerful opponents from the Near East made this situation unstable, leading Rome to send forces to secure the country as a province of its empire.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Egypt became a province of the Roman Empire in 30 BC, following the defeat of Mark Antony and Ptolemaic Queen Cleopatra VII by Octavian (later Emperor Augustus) in the Battle of Actium.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Romans relied heavily on grain shipments from Egypt, and the Roman army, under the control of a prefect appointed by the emperor, quelled rebellions, strictly enforced the collection of heavy taxes, and prevented attacks by bandits, which had become a notorious problem during the period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Alexandria became an increasingly important center on the trade route with the orient, as exotic luxuries were in high demand in Rome.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Upper Egypt frequently operated with a degree of de facto independence due to its distance from Alexandria, its strong local priesthoods, and active resistance to Roman rule, like the Revolt of Thebes (c.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] 30–29 BC), which took place immediately following the war.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The region near the southern border maintained a unique position, acting as a bridge to Nubia, with local elites sometimes exerting control over the Eastern Desert.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Although the Romans had a more hostile attitude than the Greeks towards the Egyptians, some traditions such as mummification and worship of the traditional gods continued.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The art of mummy portraiture flourished, and some Roman emperors had themselves depicted as pharaohs, though not to the extent that the Ptolemies had.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The former lived outside Egypt and did not perform the ceremonial functions of Egyptian kingship.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Local administration became Roman in style and closed to native Egyptians.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] From the mid-first century AD, Christianity took root in Egypt and it was originally seen as another cult that could be accepted.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] However, it was an uncompromising religion that sought to win converts from the pagan Egyptian and Greco-Roman religions and threatened popular religious traditions.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] This led to the persecution of converts to Christianity, culminating in the great purges of Diocletian starting in 303, but eventually Christianity won out.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] In 391, the Christian emperor Theodosius I introduced legislation that banned pagan rites and closed temples.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Alexandria became the scene of great anti-pagan riots with public and private religious imagery destroyed.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] As a consequence, Egypt's native religious culture was continually in decline.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] While the native population continued to speak their language, the ability to read hieroglyphic writing slowly disappeared as the role of the Egyptian temple priests and priestesses diminished.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The temples themselves were sometimes converted to churches or abandoned to the desert.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The pharaoh was the absolute monarch of the country and, at least in theory, wielded complete control of the land and its resources.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The king was the supreme military commander and head of the government, who relied on a bureaucracy of officials to manage his affairs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] In charge of the administration was his second in command, the vizier, who acted as the king's representative and coordinated land surveys, the treasury, building projects, the legal system, and the archives.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] At a regional level, the country was divided into as many as 42 administrative regions called nomes each governed by a nomarch, who was accountable to the vizier for his jurisdiction.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The temples formed the backbone of the economy.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Not only were they places of worship, but were also responsible for collecting and storing the kingdom's wealth in a system of granaries and treasuries administered by overseers, who redistributed grain and goods.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Much of the economy was centrally organized and strictly controlled.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Although the ancient Egyptians did not use coinage until the Late period, they did use a type of money-barter system, with standard sacks of grain and the *deben*, a weight of roughly 91 g (3 oz) of copper or silver, forming a common denominator.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Workers were paid in grain: A simple laborer might earn 5+1⁄2 sacks or ca.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] 200 kg (440 lb) of grain per month, while a foreman might earn 7+1⁄2 sacks or roughly 250 kg (550 lb).
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Prices were fixed across the country and recorded in lists to facilitate trading; for example a shirt cost five copper deben, while a cow cost 140 deben.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Grain could be traded for other goods, according to the fixed price list.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] During the fifth century BC coined money was introduced into Egypt from abroad.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] At first the coins were used as standardized pieces of precious metal rather than true money, but in the following centuries international traders came to rely on coinage.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Egyptian society was highly stratified, and social status was expressly displayed.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Farmers made up the bulk of the population, but agricultural produce was owned directly by the state, temple, or noble family that owned the land.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Farmers were also subject to a labor tax and were required to work on irrigation or construction projects in a corvée system.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Artists and craftsmen were of higher status than farmers, but they were also under state control, working in the shops attached to the temples and paid directly from the state treasury.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Scribes and officials formed the upper class in ancient Egypt, known as the "white kilt class" in reference to the bleached linen garments that served as a mark of their rank.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The upper class prominently displayed their social status in art and literature.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Below the nobility were the priests, physicians, and engineers with specialized training in their field.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] It is unclear whether slavery as understood today existed in ancient Egypt; there is difference of opinions among authors.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The ancient Egyptians viewed men and women, including people from all social classes, as essentially equal under the law, and even the lowliest peasant was entitled to petition the vizier and his court for redress.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Although slaves were mostly used as indentured servants, they were able to buy and sell their servitude, work their way to freedom or nobility, and were usually treated by doctors in the workplace.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Both men and women had the right to own and sell property, make contracts, marry and divorce, receive inheritance, and pursue legal disputes in court.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Married couples could own property jointly and protect themselves from divorce by agreeing to marriage contracts, which stipulated the financial obligations of the husband to his wife and children should the marriage end.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Compared with their counterparts in ancient Greece, Rome, and even more modern places around the world, ancient Egyptian women had a greater range of personal choices, legal rights, and opportunities for achievement.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Women such as Hatshepsut and Cleopatra VII even became pharaohs, while others wielded power as Divine Wives of Amun.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Despite these freedoms, ancient Egyptian women did not often take part in official roles in the administration, aside from the royal high priestesses, apparently served only secondary roles in the temples (not much data for many dynasties), and were less likely to be as educated as men.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The head of the legal system was officially the pharaoh, who was responsible for enacting laws, delivering justice, and maintaining law and order, a concept the ancient Egyptians referred to as Ma'at.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Although no legal codes from ancient Egypt survive, court documents show that Egyptian law was based on a common-sense view of right and wrong that emphasized reaching agreements and resolving conflicts rather than strictly adhering to a complicated set of statutes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Local councils of elders, known as *Kenbet* in the New Kingdom, were responsible for ruling in court cases involving small claims and minor disputes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] More serious cases involving murder, major land transactions, and tomb robbery were referred to the *Great Kenbet*, over which the vizier or pharaoh presided.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Plaintiffs and defendants were expected to represent themselves and were required to swear an oath that they had told the truth.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] In some cases, the state took on both the role of prosecutor and judge, and it could torture the accused with beatings to obtain a confession and the names of any co-conspirators.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Whether the charges were trivial or serious, court scribes documented the complaint, testimony, and verdict of the case for future reference.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Punishment for minor crimes involved either imposition of fines, beatings, facial mutilation, or exile, depending on the severity of the offense.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Serious crimes such as murder and tomb robbery were punished by execution, carried out by decapitation, drowning, or impaling the criminal on a stake.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Punishment could also be extended to the criminal's family.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Beginning in the New Kingdom, oracles played a major role in the legal system, dispensing justice in both civil and criminal cases.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The procedure was to ask the god a "yes" or "no" question concerning the right or wrong of an issue.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The god, carried by a number of priests, rendered judgement by choosing one or the other, moving forward or backward, or pointing to one of the answers written on a piece of papyrus or an ostracon.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] A combination of favorable geographical features contributed to the success of ancient Egyptian culture, the most important of which was the rich fertile soil resulting from annual inundations of the Nile River.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The ancient Egyptians were thus able to produce an abundance of food, allowing the population to devote more time and resources to cultural, technological, and artistic pursuits.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Land management was crucial in ancient Egypt because taxes were assessed based on the amount of land a person owned.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Farming in Egypt was dependent on the cycle of the Nile River.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Egyptians recognized three seasons: *Akhet* (flooding), *Peret* (planting), and *Shemu* (harvesting).
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The flooding season lasted from June to September, depositing on the river's banks a layer of mineral-rich silt ideal for growing crops.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] After the floodwaters had receded, the growing season lasted from October to February.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Farmers plowed and planted seeds in the fields, which were irrigated with ditches and canals.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Egypt received little rainfall, so farmers relied on the Nile to water their crops.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] From March to May, farmers used sickles to harvest their crops, which were then threshed with a flail to separate the straw from the grain.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Winnowing removed the chaff from the grain, and the grain was then ground into flour, brewed to make beer, or stored for later use.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The ancient Egyptians cultivated emmer and barley, and several other cereal grains, all of which were used to make the two main food staples of bread and beer.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Flax plants, uprooted before they started flowering, were grown for the fibers of their stems.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] These fibers were split along their length and spun into thread, which was used to weave sheets of linen and to make clothing.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Papyrus growing on the banks of the Nile River was used to make paper.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Vegetables and fruits were grown in garden plots, close to habitations and on higher ground, and had to be watered by hand.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Vegetables included leeks, garlic, melons, squashes, pulses, lettuce, and other crops, in addition to grapes that were made into wine.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Egyptians believed that a balanced relationship between people and animals was an essential element of the cosmic order; thus humans, animals and plants were believed to be members of a single whole.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Animals, both domesticated and wild, were therefore a critical source of spirituality, companionship, and sustenance to the ancient Egyptians.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Cattle were the most important livestock; the administration collected taxes on livestock in regular censuses, and the size of a herd reflected the prestige and importance of the estate or temple that owned them.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] In addition to cattle, the ancient Egyptians kept sheep, goats, and pigs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Poultry, such as ducks, geese, and pigeons, were captured in nets and bred on farms, where they were force-fed with dough to fatten them.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Nile provided a plentiful source of fish.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Bees were also domesticated from at least the Old Kingdom, and provided both honey and wax.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The ancient Egyptians used donkeys and oxen as beasts of burden, and they were responsible for plowing the fields and trampling seed into the soil.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The slaughter of a fattened ox was also a central part of an offering ritual.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Horses were introduced by the Hyksos in the Second Intermediate Period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Camels, although known from the New Kingdom, were not used as beasts of burden until the Late Period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] There is also evidence to suggest that elephants were briefly used in the Late Period but largely abandoned due to lack of grazing land.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Cats, dogs, and monkeys were common family pets, while more exotic pets imported from the heart of Africa, such as Sub-Saharan African lions, were reserved for royalty.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Herodotus observed that the Egyptians were the only people to keep their animals with them in their houses.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] During the Late Period, the worship of the gods in their animal form was extremely popular, such as the cat goddess Bastet and the ibis god Thoth, and these animals were kept in large numbers for the purpose of ritual sacrifice.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Egypt is rich in building and decorative stone, copper and lead ores, gold, and semiprecious stones.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] These natural resources allowed the ancient Egyptians to build monuments, sculpt statues, make tools, and fashion jewelry.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Embalmers used salts from the Wadi Natrun for mummification, which also provided the gypsum needed to make plaster.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Ore-bearing rock formations were found in distant, inhospitable wadis in the Eastern Desert and the Sinai, requiring large, state-controlled expeditions to obtain natural resources found there.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] There were extensive gold mines in Nubia, and one of the first maps known is of a gold mine in this region.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Wadi Hammamat was a notable source of granite, greywacke, and gold.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Flint was the first mineral collected and used to make tools, and flint handaxes are the earliest pieces of evidence of habitation in the Nile valley.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Nodules of the mineral were carefully flaked to make blades and arrowheads of moderate hardness and durability even after copper was adopted for this purpose.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Ancient Egyptians were among the first to use minerals such as sulfur as cosmetic substances.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Egyptians worked deposits of the lead ore galena at Gebel Rosas to make net sinkers, plumb bobs, and small figurines.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Copper was the most important metal for toolmaking in ancient Egypt and was smelted in furnaces from malachite ore mined in the Sinai.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Workers collected gold by washing the nuggets out of sediment in alluvial deposits, or by the more labor-intensive process of grinding and washing gold-bearing quartzite.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Iron deposits found in upper Egypt were used in the Late Period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] High-quality building stones were abundant in Egypt; the ancient Egyptians quarried limestone all along the Nile valley, granite from Aswan, and basalt and sandstone from the wadis of the Eastern Desert.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Deposits of decorative stones such as porphyry, greywacke, alabaster, and carnelian dotted the Eastern Desert and were collected even before the First Dynasty.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] In the Ptolemaic and Roman Periods, miners worked deposits of emeralds in Wadi Sikait and amethyst in Wadi el-Hudi.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The ancient Egyptians engaged in trade with their foreign neighbors to obtain rare, exotic goods not found in Egypt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] In the Predynastic Period, they established trade with Nubia to obtain gold and incense.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] They also established trade with Palestine, as evidenced by Palestinian-style oil jugs found in the burials of the First Dynasty pharaohs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] An Egyptian colony stationed in southern Canaan dates to slightly before the First Dynasty.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Tell es-Sakan in present-day Gaza was established as an Egyptian settlement in the late 4th millennium BC, and is theorised to have been the main Egyptian colonial site in the region.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Narmer had Egyptian pottery produced in Canaan and exported back to Egypt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] By the Second Dynasty at latest, ancient Egyptian trade with Byblos yielded a critical source of quality timber not found in Egypt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] By the Fifth Dynasty, trade with Punt provided gold, aromatic resins, ebony, ivory, and wild animals such as monkeys and baboons.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Egypt relied on trade with Anatolia for essential quantities of tin as well as supplementary supplies of copper, both metals being necessary for the manufacture of bronze.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The ancient Egyptians prized the blue stone lapis lazuli, which had to be imported from far-away Afghanistan.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Egypt's Mediterranean trade partners also included Greece and Crete, which provided, among other goods, supplies of olive oil.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Egyptian language is a northern Afro-Asiatic language closely related to the Berber and Semitic languages.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Ancient Egyptian language likewise shared linguistic ties with other Afro-Asiatic languages such as the Chadic languages of west and central Africa, the Cushitic languages of northeast Africa, and the Ethio-Semitic languages, which are found in Ethiopia and Eritrea.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Many scholars have accepted an African phylum language origin since five of the six Afro-Asiatic subfamilies, including the Egyptian language, are spoken on the African continent, and only one in Asia.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] It has the longest known history of any language having been written from c.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] 3200 BC to the Middle Ages and remaining as a spoken language for longer.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The phases of ancient Egyptian are Old Egyptian, Middle Egyptian (Classical Egyptian), Late Egyptian, Demotic and Coptic.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Egyptian writings do not show dialect differences before Coptic, but it was probably spoken in regional dialects around Memphis and later Thebes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Ancient Egyptian was a synthetic language, but it became more analytic later on.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Late Egyptian developed prefixal definite and indefinite articles, which replaced the older inflectional suffixes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] There was a change from the older verb–subject–object word order to subject–verb–object.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Egyptian hieroglyphic, hieratic, and demotic scripts were eventually replaced by the more phonetic Coptic alphabet.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Coptic is still used in the liturgy of the Egyptian Orthodox Church, and traces of it are found in modern Egyptian Arabic.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Ancient Egyptian has 25 consonants similar to those of other Afro-Asiatic languages.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] These include pharyngeal and emphatic consonants, voiced and voiceless stops, voiceless fricatives and voiced and voiceless affricates.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] It has three long and three short vowels, which expanded in Late Egyptian to about nine.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The basic word in Egyptian, similar to Semitic and Berber, is a triliteral or biliteral root of consonants and semiconsonants.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The verb conjugation corresponds to the person.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] For example, the triconsonantal skeleton ***S-Ḏ-M*** is the semantic core of the word 'hear'; its basic conjugation is **sḏm**, 'he hears'.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] If the subject is a noun, suffixes are not added to the verb: **sḏm ḥmt**, 'the woman hears'.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Adjectives are derived from nouns through a process that Egyptologists call *nisbation* because of its similarity with Arabic.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The word order is predicate–subject in verbal and adjectival sentences, and subject–predicate in nominal and adverbial sentences.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The subject can be moved to the beginning of sentences if it is long and is followed by a resumptive pronoun.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Verbs and nouns are negated by the particle *n*, but *nn* is used for adverbial and adjectival sentences.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Stress falls on the ultimate or penultimate syllable, which can be open (CV) or closed (CVC).
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] 3000 BC, and is composed of hundreds of symbols.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] A hieroglyph can represent a word, a sound, or a silent determinative; and the same symbol can serve different purposes in different contexts.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Hieroglyphs were a formal script, used on stone monuments and in tombs, that could be as detailed as individual works of art.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] In day-to-day writing, scribes used a cursive form of writing, called hieratic, which was quicker and easier.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] While formal hieroglyphs may be read in rows or columns in either direction (though typically written from right to left), hieratic was always written from right to left, usually in horizontal rows.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] A new form of writing, Demotic, became the prevalent writing style, and it is this form of writing—along with formal hieroglyphs—that accompany the Greek text on the Rosetta Stone.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Around the first century AD, the Coptic alphabet started to be used alongside the Demotic script.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Coptic is a modified Greek alphabet with the addition of some Demotic signs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Although formal hieroglyphs were used in a ceremonial role until the fourth century, towards the end only a small handful of priests could still read them.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] As the traditional religious establishments were disbanded, knowledge of hieroglyphic writing was mostly lost.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Attempts to decipher them date to the Byzantine and Islamic periods in Egypt, but only in the 1820s, after the discovery of the Rosetta Stone and years of research by Thomas Young and Jean-François Champollion, were hieroglyphs substantially deciphered.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Writing first appeared in association with kingship on labels and tags for items found in royal tombs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] It was primarily an occupation of the scribes, who worked out of the *Per Ankh* institution or the House of Life.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The latter comprised offices, libraries (called House of Books), laboratories and observatories.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Some of the best-known pieces of ancient Egyptian literature, such as the Pyramid and Coffin Texts, were written in Classical Egyptian, which continued to be the language of writing until about 1300 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Late Egyptian was spoken from the New Kingdom onward and is represented in Ramesside administrative documents, love poetry and tales, as well as in Demotic and Coptic texts.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] During this period, the tradition of writing had evolved into the tomb autobiography, such as those of Harkhuf and Weni.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The genre known as *Sebayt* ('instructions') was developed to communicate teachings and guidance from famous nobles; the Ipuwer papyrus, a poem of lamentations describing natural disasters and social upheaval, is a famous example.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The *Story of Sinuhe*, written in Middle Egyptian, might be the classic of Egyptian literature.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Also written at this time was the Westcar Papyrus, a set of stories told to Khufu by his sons relating the marvels performed by priests.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The Instruction of Amenemope is considered a masterpiece of Near Eastern literature.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Towards the end of the New Kingdom, the vernacular language was more often employed to write popular pieces such as the Story of Wenamun and the Instruction of Any.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] The former tells the story of a noble who is robbed on his way to buy cedar from Lebanon and of his struggle to return to Egypt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] From about 700 BC, narrative stories and instructions, such as the popular Instructions of Onchsheshonqy, as well as personal and business documents were written in the demotic script and phase of Egyptian.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p01] Many stories written in demotic during the Greco-Roman period were set in previous historical eras, when Egypt was an independent nation ruled by great pharaohs such as Ramesses II.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Most ancient Egyptians were farmers tied to the land.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Their dwellings were restricted to immediate family members, and were constructed of mudbrick designed to remain cool in the heat of the day.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Each home had a kitchen with an open roof, which contained a grindstone for milling grain and a small oven for baking the bread.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Ceramics served as household wares for the storage, preparation, transport, and consumption of food, drink, and raw materials.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Walls were painted white and could be covered with dyed linen wall hangings.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Floors were covered with reed mats, while wooden stools, beds raised from the floor and individual tables comprised the furniture.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The ancient Egyptians placed a great value on hygiene and appearance.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Most bathed in the Nile and used a pasty soap made from animal fat and chalk.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Men shaved their entire bodies for cleanliness; perfumes and aromatic ointments covered bad odors and soothed skin.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Clothing was made from simple linen sheets that were bleached white, and both men and women of the upper classes wore wigs, jewelry, and cosmetics.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Children went without clothing until maturity, at about age 12, and at this age males were circumcised and had their heads shaved.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Mothers were responsible for taking care of the children, while the father provided the family's income.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Music and dance were popular entertainments for those who could afford them.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Early instruments included flutes and harps, while instruments similar to trumpets, oboes, and pipes developed later and became popular.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In the New Kingdom, the Egyptians played on bells, cymbals, tambourines, drums, and imported lutes and lyres from Asia.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The sistrum was a rattle-like musical instrument that was especially important in religious ceremonies.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The ancient Egyptians enjoyed a variety of leisure activities, including games and music.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Senet, a board game where pieces moved according to random chance, was particularly popular from the earliest times; another similar game was mehen, which had a circular gaming board.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] "Hounds and Jackals," also known as 58 holes, is another example of board games played in ancient Egypt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The first complete set of this game was discovered from a Theban tomb of the Egyptian pharaoh Amenemhat IV that dates to the 13th Dynasty.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Juggling and ball games were popular with children, and wrestling is also documented in a tomb at Beni Hasan.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The wealthy members of ancient Egyptian society enjoyed hunting, fishing, and boating as well.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The excavation of the workers' village of Deir el-Medina has resulted in one of the most thoroughly documented accounts of community life in the ancient world, which spans almost four hundred years.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] There is no comparable site in which the organization, social interactions, and working and living conditions of a community have been studied in such detail.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Egyptian cuisine remained remarkably stable over time; indeed, the cuisine of modern Egypt retains some striking similarities to the cuisine of the ancients.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The staple diet consisted of bread and beer, supplemented with vegetables such as onions and garlic, and fruit such as dates and figs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Wine and meat were enjoyed by all on feast days while the upper classes indulged on a more regular basis.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Fish, meat, and fowl could be salted or dried, and could be cooked in stews or roasted on a grill.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The architecture of ancient Egypt includes some of the most famous structures in the world: the Great Pyramids of Giza and the temples at Thebes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Building projects were organized and funded by the state for religious and commemorative purposes, but also to reinforce the wide-ranging power of the pharaoh.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The ancient Egyptians were skilled builders; using only simple but effective tools and sighting instruments, architects could build large stone structures with great accuracy and precision that is still envied today.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The domestic dwellings of elite and ordinary Egyptians alike were constructed from perishable materials such as mudbricks and wood, and have not survived.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Peasants lived in simple homes, while the palaces of the elite and the pharaoh were more elaborate structures.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] A few surviving New Kingdom palaces, such as those in Malkata and Amarna, show richly decorated walls and floors with scenes of people, birds, water pools, deities and geometric designs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Important structures such as temples and tombs that were intended to last forever were constructed of stone instead of mudbricks.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The architectural elements used in the world's first large-scale stone building, Djoser's mortuary complex, include post and lintel supports in the papyrus and lotus motif.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The earliest preserved ancient Egyptian temples, such as those at Giza, consist of single, enclosed halls with roof slabs supported by columns.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In the New Kingdom, architects added the pylon, the open courtyard, and the enclosed hypostyle hall to the front of the temple's sanctuary, a style that was standard until the Greco-Roman period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The earliest and most popular tomb architecture in the Old Kingdom was the mastaba, a flat-roofed rectangular structure of mudbrick or stone built over an underground burial chamber.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The step pyramid of Djoser is a series of stone mastabas stacked on top of each other.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Pyramids were built during the Old and Middle Kingdoms, but most later rulers abandoned them in favor of less conspicuous rock-cut tombs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The use of the pyramid form continued in private tomb chapels of the New Kingdom and in the royal pyramids of Nubia.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The ancient Egyptians produced art to serve functional purposes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] For over 3500 years, artists adhered to artistic forms and iconography that were developed during the Old Kingdom, following a strict set of principles that resisted foreign influence and internal change.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] These artistic standards—simple lines, shapes, and flat areas of color combined with the characteristic flat projection of figures with no indication of spatial depth—created a sense of order and balance within a composition.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Images and text were intimately interwoven on tomb and temple walls, coffins, stelae, and even statues.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The Narmer Palette, for example, displays figures that can also be read as hieroglyphs.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Because of the rigid rules that governed its highly stylized and symbolic appearance, ancient Egyptian art served its political and religious purposes with precision and clarity.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Ancient Egyptian artisans used stone as a medium for carving statues and fine reliefs, but used wood as a cheap and easily carved substitute.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Paints were obtained from minerals such as iron ores (red and yellow ochres), copper ores (blue and green), soot or charcoal (black), and limestone (white).
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Paints could be mixed with gum arabic as a binder and pressed into cakes, which could be moistened with water when needed.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Pharaohs used reliefs to record victories in battle, royal decrees, and religious scenes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Common citizens had access to pieces of funerary art, such as ushabti statues and books of the dead, which they believed would protect them in the afterlife.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] During the Middle Kingdom, wooden or clay models depicting scenes from everyday life became popular additions to the tomb.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In an attempt to duplicate the activities of the living in the afterlife, these models show laborers, houses, boats, and even military formations that are scale representations of the ideal ancient Egyptian afterlife.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Despite the homogeneity of ancient Egyptian art, the styles of particular times and places sometimes reflected changing cultural or political attitudes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] After the invasion of the Hyksos in the Second Intermediate Period, Minoan-style frescoes were found in Avaris.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The most striking example of a politically driven change in artistic forms comes from the Amarna Period, where figures were radically altered to conform to Akhenaten's revolutionary religious ideas.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] This style, known as Amarna art, was quickly abandoned after Akhenaten's death and replaced by the traditional forms.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Beliefs in the divine and in the afterlife were ingrained in ancient Egyptian civilization from its inception; pharaonic rule was based on the divine right of kings.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The Egyptian pantheon was populated by gods who had supernatural powers and were called on for help or protection.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] However, the gods were not always viewed as benevolent, and Egyptians believed they had to be appeased with offerings and prayers.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The structure of this pantheon changed continually as new deities were promoted in the hierarchy, but priests made no effort to organize the diverse and sometimes conflicting myths and stories into a coherent system.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] These various conceptions of divinity were not considered contradictory but rather layers in the multiple facets of reality.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Gods were worshiped in cult temples administered by priests acting on the king's behalf.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] At the center of the temple was the cult statue in a shrine.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Temples were not places of public worship or congregation, and only on select feast days and celebrations was a shrine carrying the statue of the god brought out for public worship.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Normally, the god's domain was sealed off from the outside world and was only accessible to temple officials.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Common citizens could worship private statues in their homes, and amulets offered protection against the forces of chaos.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] After the New Kingdom, the pharaoh's role as a spiritual intermediary was de-emphasized as religious customs shifted to direct worship of the gods.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] As a result, priests developed a system of oracles to communicate the will of the gods directly to the people.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The Egyptians believed that every human being was composed of physical and spiritual parts or *aspects*.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In addition to the body, each person had a *šwt* (shadow), a *ba* (personality or soul), a *ka* (life-force), and a *name*.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The heart, rather than the brain, was considered the seat of thoughts and emotions.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] After death, the spiritual aspects were released from the body and could move at will, but they required the physical remains (or a substitute, such as a statue) as a permanent home.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The ultimate goal of the deceased was to rejoin his *ka* and *ba* and become one of the "blessed dead", living on as an *akh*, or "effective one".
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] For this to happen, the deceased had to be judged worthy in a trial, in which the heart was weighed against a "feather of truth".
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] If deemed worthy, the deceased could continue their existence on earth in spiritual form.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] If they were not deemed worthy, their heart was eaten by Ammit the Devourer and they were erased from the Universe.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The ancient Egyptians maintained an elaborate set of burial customs that they believed were necessary to ensure immortality after death.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] These customs involved preserving the body by mummification, performing burial ceremonies, and interring with the body goods the deceased would use in the afterlife.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Before the Old Kingdom, bodies buried in desert pits were naturally preserved by desiccation.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The arid, desert conditions were a boon throughout the history of ancient Egypt for burials of the poor, who could not afford the elaborate burial preparations available to the elite.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Wealthier Egyptians began to bury their dead in stone tombs and use artificial mummification, which involved removing the internal organs, wrapping the body in linen, and burying it in a rectangular stone sarcophagus or wooden coffin.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Beginning in the Fourth Dynasty, some parts were preserved separately in canopic jars.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] By the New Kingdom, the ancient Egyptians had perfected the art of mummification; the best technique took 70 days and involved removing the internal organs, removing the brain through the nose, and desiccating the body in a mixture of salts called natron.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The body was then wrapped in linen with protective amulets inserted between layers and placed in a decorated anthropoid coffin.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Mummies of the Late Period were also placed in painted cartonnage mummy cases.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Actual preservation practices declined during the Ptolemaic and Roman eras, while greater emphasis was placed on the outer appearance of the mummy, which was decorated.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Wealthy Egyptians were buried with larger quantities of luxury items, but all burials, regardless of social status, included goods for the deceased.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Funerary texts were often included in the grave, and, beginning in the New Kingdom, so were ushabti statues that were believed to perform manual labor for them in the afterlife.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Rituals in which the deceased was magically re-animated accompanied burials.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] After burial, living relatives were expected to occasionally bring food to the tomb and recite prayers on behalf of the deceased.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The ancient Egyptian military was responsible for defending Egypt against foreign invasion, and for maintaining Egypt's domination in the ancient Near East.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The military protected mining expeditions to the Sinai during the Old Kingdom and fought civil wars during the First and Second Intermediate Periods.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The military was responsible for maintaining fortifications along important trade routes, such as those found at the city of Buhen on the way to Nubia.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Forts also were constructed to serve as military bases, such as the fortress at Sile, which was a base of operations for expeditions to the Levant.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In the New Kingdom, a series of pharaohs used the standing Egyptian army to attack and conquer Kush and parts of the Levant.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Typical military equipment included bows and arrows, spears, and round-topped shields made by stretching animal skin over a wooden frame.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In the New Kingdom, the military began using chariots that had earlier been introduced by the Hyksos invaders.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Weapons and armor continued to improve after the adoption of bronze: shields were now made from solid wood with a bronze buckle, spears were tipped with a bronze point, and the khopesh was adopted from Asiatic soldiers.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The pharaoh was usually depicted in art and literature riding at the head of the army; it has been suggested that at least a few pharaohs, such as Seqenenre Tao II and his sons, did do so.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] However, it has also been argued that "kings of this period did not personally act as frontline war leaders, fighting alongside their troops".
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Soldiers were recruited from the general population, but during, and especially after, the New Kingdom, mercenaries from Nubia, Kush, and Libya were hired to fight for Egypt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In technology, medicine, and mathematics, ancient Egypt achieved a relatively high standard of productivity and sophistication.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Traditional empiricism, as evidenced by the Edwin Smith and Ebers papyri (c.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The Egyptians created their own alphabet and decimal system.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Even before the Old Kingdom, the ancient Egyptians had developed a glassy material known as faience, which they treated as a type of artificial semi-precious stone.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Faience is a non-clay ceramic made of silica, small amounts of lime and soda, and a colorant, typically copper.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The material was used to make beads, tiles, figurines, and small wares.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Several methods can be used to create faience, but typically production involved application of the powdered materials in the form of a paste over a clay core, which was then fired.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] By a related technique, the ancient Egyptians produced a pigment known as Egyptian blue, also called blue frit, which is produced by fusing (or sintering) silica, copper, lime, and an alkali such as natron.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The product can be ground up and used as a pigment.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The ancient Egyptians could fabricate a wide variety of objects from glass with great skill, but it is not clear whether they developed the process independently.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] It is also unclear whether they made their own raw glass or merely imported pre-made ingots, which they melted and finished.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] However, they did have technical expertise in making objects, as well as adding trace elements to control the color of the finished glass.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] A range of colors could be produced, including yellow, red, green, blue, purple, and white, and the glass could be made either transparent or opaque.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The medical problems of the ancient Egyptians stemmed directly from their environment.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Living and working close to the Nile brought hazards from malaria and debilitating schistosomiasis parasites, which caused liver and intestinal damage.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Dangerous wildlife such as crocodiles and hippos were also a common threat.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The lifelong labors of farming and building put stress on the spine and joints, and traumatic injuries from construction and warfare all took a significant toll on the body.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The grit and sand from stone-ground flour abraded teeth, leaving them susceptible to abscesses (though caries were rare).
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The diets of the wealthy were rich in sugars, which promoted periodontal disease.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Despite the flattering physiques portrayed on tomb walls, the overweight mummies of many of the upper class show the effects of a life of overindulgence.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Adult life expectancy was about 35 for men and 30 for women, but reaching adulthood was difficult as about one-third of the population died in infancy.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Ancient Egyptian physicians were renowned in the ancient Near East for their healing skills, and some, such as Imhotep, remained famous long after their deaths.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Herodotus remarked that there was a high degree of specialization among Egyptian physicians, with some treating only the head or the stomach, while others were eye-doctors and dentists.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Training of physicians took place at the *Per Ankh* or "House of Life" institution, most notably those headquartered in Per-Bastet during the New Kingdom and at Abydos and Saïs in the Late period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Medical papyri show empirical knowledge of anatomy, injuries, and practical treatments.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Wounds were treated by bandaging with raw meat, white linen, sutures, nets, pads, and swabs soaked with honey to prevent infection, while opium, thyme, and belladona were used to relieve pain.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The earliest records of burn treatment describe burn dressings that use the milk from mothers of male babies.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Moldy bread, honey, and copper salts were also used to prevent infection from dirt in burns.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Garlic and onions were used regularly to promote good health and were thought to relieve asthma symptoms.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Ancient Egyptian surgeons stitched wounds, set broken bones, and amputated diseased limbs, but they recognized that some injuries were so serious that they could only make the patient comfortable until death occurred.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Early Egyptians knew how to assemble planks of wood into a ship hull and had mastered advanced forms of shipbuilding as early as 3000 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The Archaeological Institute of America reports that the oldest planked ships known are the Abydos boats.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] A group of 14 discovered ships in Abydos were constructed of wooden planks "sewn" together.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Discovered by Egyptologist David O'Connor of New York University, woven straps were found to have been used to lash the planks together, and reeds or grass stuffed between the planks helped to seal the seams.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Because the ships are all buried together and near a mortuary belonging to Pharaoh Khasekhemwy, originally they were all thought to have belonged to him, but one of the 14 ships dates to 3000 BC, and the associated pottery jars buried with the vessels also suggest earlier dating.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The ship dating to 3000 BC was 75 feet (23 m) long and is now thought to perhaps have belonged to an earlier pharaoh, perhaps one as early as Hor-Aha.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Early Egyptians also knew how to assemble planks of wood with treenails to fasten them together, using pitch for caulking the seams.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The "Khufu ship", a 43.6-metre (143 ft) vessel sealed into a pit in the Giza pyramid complex at the foot of the Great Pyramid of Giza in the Fourth Dynasty around 2500 BC, is a full-size surviving example that may have filled the symbolic function of a solar barque.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Early Egyptians also knew how to fasten the planks of this ship together with mortise and tenon joints.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Large seagoing ships are known to have been heavily used by the Egyptians in their trade with the city states of the eastern Mediterranean, especially Byblos (on the coast of modern-day Lebanon), and in several expeditions down the Red Sea to the Land of Punt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In fact one of the earliest Egyptian words for a seagoing ship is a "Byblos Ship", which originally defined a class of Egyptian seagoing ships used on the Byblos run; however, by the end of the Old Kingdom, the term had come to include large seagoing ships, whatever their destination.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In 1977, an ancient north–south canal was discovered extending from Lake Timsah to the Ballah Lakes.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] It was dated to the Middle Kingdom of Egypt by extrapolating dates of ancient sites constructed along its course.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In 2011, archaeologists from Italy, the United States, and Egypt, excavating a dried-up lagoon known as Mersa Gawasis, unearthed traces of an ancient harbor that once launched early voyages, such as Hatshepsut's Punt, expedition onto the open ocean.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Some of the site's most evocative evidence for the ancient Egyptians' seafaring prowess include large ship timbers and hundreds of feet of ropes, made from papyrus, coiled in huge bundles.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In 2013, a team of Franco-Egyptian archaeologists discovered what is believed to be the world's oldest port, dating back about 4500 years, from the time of King Khufu, on the Red Sea coast, near Wadi el-Jarf (about 110 miles south of Suez).
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The earliest attested examples of mathematical calculations date to the predynastic Naqada period, and show a fully developed numeral system.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The importance of mathematics to an educated Egyptian is suggested by a New Kingdom fictional letter in which the writer proposes a scholarly competition between himself and another scribe regarding everyday calculation tasks such as accounting of land, labor, and grain.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] They understood basic concepts of algebra and geometry, and could solve systems of equations.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Nubians also exercised a trigonometric methodology comparable to their Egyptian counterparts.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Mathematical notation was decimal, and based on hieroglyphic signs for each power of ten up to one million.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Each of these could be written as many times as necessary to add up to the desired number; so to write the number eighty or eight hundred, the symbol for ten or one hundred was written eight times respectively.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Because their methods of calculation could not handle most fractions with a numerator greater than one, they had to write fractions as the sum of several fractions.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] For example, they resolved the fraction *two-fifths* into the sum of *one-third* + *one-fifteenth*.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Standard tables of values facilitated this.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Some common fractions, however, were written with a special glyph—the equivalent of the modern two-thirds is shown on the right.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Ancient Egyptian mathematicians knew the Pythagorean theorem as an empirical formula.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] They were aware, for example, that a triangle had a right angle opposite the hypotenuse when its sides were in a 3–4–5 ratio.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] a reasonable approximation of the formula **π***r*2.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Estimates of the size of the population range from 1–1.5 million in the 3rd millennium BC to possibly 2–3 million by the 1st millennium BC, before growing significantly towards the end of that millennium.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] International scholarship reflected in the UNESCO General History of Africa book series have expressed a similar position.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] A majority of the scholars that contributed to the Volume II edition (1981) considered Egypt an indigenous African civilisation with a mixed population that originated largely in the Sahara and featured a variety of skin colours from north and south of the Saharan region.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In the view of Egyptian scholar and featured editor, Gamal Mokhtar, Upper Egypt and Nubia held "similar ethnic composition" with comparable material culture.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] An updated Volume IX publication launched in 2025, reaffirmed the view that Egypt had African and Eurasian populations.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The review section which focused on the 1974 "Peopling of Egypt" symposium stated that accumulated research over three decades had confirmed the migration from Southernly African along with Saharan populations into the early Nile Valley.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Upper Egypt was now positioned as a origin point of Pharaonic unification, with supporting archaeological, anthropological, genetic and linguistic sources of evidence having identified close affinities between Upper Egypt and other Sub-Saharan African populations.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] According to historian William Stiebling and archaeologist Susan N.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Helft, conflicting DNA analysis on recent genetic samples such as the Amarna royal mummies has led to a lack of consensus on the genetic makeup of the ancient Egyptians and their geographic origins.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The genetic history of Ancient Egypt remains a developing field, and is relevant for the understanding of population demographic events connecting Africa and Eurasia.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] To date, the amount of genome-wide aDNA analyses on ancient specimens from Egypt and Sudan remain scarce, although studies on uniparental haplogroups in ancient individuals have been carried out several times, pointing broadly to affinities with other African and Eurasian groups.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Before this study, whole-genome sequencing of ancient Egyptians from the early periods of Egyptian Dynastic history had not yet been accomplished, mainly because of the problematic DNA preservation conditions in Egypt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The corpse had been placed intact in a large circular clay pot without embalming, and then installed inside a cliff tomb, which accounts for the comparatively good level of conservation of the skeleton and its DNA.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Most of his genome was found to be associated with North African Neolithic ancestry, but about 20% of his genetic ancestry could be sourced to the eastern Fertile Crescent, including Mesopotamia.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Overall, the 2025 study "provides direct evidence of genetic ancestry related to the eastern Fertile Crescent in ancient Egypt".
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] This genetic connection suggests that there had been ancient migration flows from the eastern Fertile Crescent to Egypt, in addition to the exchanges of objects and imagery (domesticated animals and plants, writing systems...) already observed.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] This suggests a pattern of wide cultural and demographic expansion from the Mesopotamian region, which affected both Anatolia and Egypt during this period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The authors acknowledged some limitations of the study, such as the results deriving from one single Egyptian genome and known limitations predicting specific phenotypic traits in understudied populations.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The analysis also excluded any substantial ancestry in the Nuwayrat genome related to a previously published 4,500-year-old hunter-gatherer genome from the Mota cave in Ethiopia, or other individuals in central, eastern, or southern Africa.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] An earlier partial genomic analyses had been made on much later specimens recovered from the Nile River Valley, Abusir el-Meleq, Egypt, dating from the 787 BC-23 AD time period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Two of the individuals were dated to the Pre-Ptolemaic Period (New Kingdom to Late Period), and one individual to the Ptolemaic Period.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] These results point to a genetic continuity of Ancient Egyptians with modern Egyptians.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The results further point to a close genetic affinity between ancient Egyptians and Middle Eastern populations, especially ancient groups from the Levant.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Ancient Egyptians also displayed affinities to Nubians to the south of Egypt, in modern-day Sudan.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Archaeological and historical evidence support interactions between Egyptian and Nubian populations more than 5000 years ago, with socio-political dynamics between Egyptians and Nubians ranging from peaceful coexistence to variably successful attempts of conquest.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] A study on sixty-six ancient Nubian individuals revealed significant contact with ancient Egyptians, characterized by the presence of c.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] 57% Neolithic/Bronze Age Levantine ancestry in these individuals.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Such geneflow of Levantine-like ancestry corresponds with archaeological and botanic evidence, pointing to a Neolithic movement around 7,000 years ago.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Modern Egyptians, like modern Nubians, also underwent subsequent admixture events, contributing both "Sub-Saharan" African-like and West Asian-like ancestries, since the Roman period, with significance on the African Slave Trade and the Spread of Islam.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Genetic analysis of a modern Upper Egyptian population in Adaima by Eric Crubézy had identified genetic markers common across Africa, with 71% of the Adaima samples carrying E1b1 haplogroup and 3% carrying the L0f mitochondrial haplogroup.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] A secondary review, published in UNESCO General History of Africa Volume IX, in 2025 noted the results were preliminary and need to be confirmed by other laboratories with new sequencing methods.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] This was supported by an anthropological study which found the notable presence of dental markers, characteristic of Khoisan people, in a predynastic-era cemetery at Adaïma.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The genetic marker E1b1 was identified in a number of genetic studies to have wide distribution across Egypt, with "P2/215/M35.1 (E1b1b), for short M35, likely also originated in eastern tropical Africa, and is predominantly distributed in an arc from the Horn of Africa up through Egypt".
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Multiple STR analyses of the Amarna royal mummies (including Rameses III, Tutankhamun and Amenhotep III) were deployed to estimate their ethnicity have found they had strong affinities with modern Sub-Saharan populations.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Nonetheless, these forms of analysis were not exhaustive as only 8 of the 13 CODIS markets were used.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Some scholars, such as Christopher Ehret, caution that a wider sampling area is needed and argue that the current data is inconclusive on the origin of ancient Egyptians.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] They also point out issues with the previously used methodology such as the sampling size, comparative approach and a "biased interpretation" of the genetic data.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] They argue in favor for a link between Ancient Egypt and the northern Horn of Africa.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] This latter view has been attributed to the corresponding archaeological, genetic, linguistic and biological anthropological sources of evidence which broadly indicate that the earliest Egyptians and Nubians were the descendants of populations in Northeast Africa.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Pharaonic Egypt featured a physical gradation across the regional populations, with Upper Egyptians having shared more biological affinities with Sudanese and southernly African populations, whereas Lower Egyptians had closer genetic links with Levantine and Mediterranean populations.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In the view of William Stiebling and Susan Helft, "some ancient Egyptians looked more Middle Eastern and others looked more Sudanese or Ethiopians of today, and some may even have looked like other groups in Africa".
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Overall, the authors reached the conclusion that Ancient Egypt was a heterogeneous civilization with bio-cultural connections across Africa and Eurasia.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Recent studies have emphasized that Ancient Egypt contained much greater ethnic diversity than traditionally assumed in earlier historical approaches.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Egyptian notions of identity were formed mainly through social constructs, rather than adhering to fixed biological groups.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Riggs and Baines note that the common ideological contrast between "Egyptian" and "Other" oversimplifies population groups which varied according to local traditions, dialects, and naming practices.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Archaeological evidence also shows foreigners lived in Egypt, particularly Nubians, Libyans and Asiatics.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] They would frequently participate in activities that which crossed the social divide described by Riggs and Baines.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Furthermore, Smith highlights that while state ideology portrayed outsiders through negative stereotypes, evidence regarding everyday interactions, intermarriage, shared foodways, and visual self-presentations demonstrate that ethnic boundaries flexible across social and political contexts.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] A number of scholars have argued that Ancient Egyptians shared cultural connections and origins with the Land of Punt.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] This has been accredited to the Egyptian textual descriptions of Puntland as *Ta Nejter* which translates into "God's Land", along with temple reliefs which depicted Puntites with reddish-brown skin complexions similar to their Egyptian counterparts.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The culture and monuments of ancient Egypt have left a lasting legacy on the world.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Egyptian civilization significantly influenced the Kingdom of Kush and Meroë with both adopting Egyptian religious and architectural norms (hundreds of pyramids (6–30 meters high) were built in Egypt/Sudan), as well as using Egyptian writing as the basis of the Meroitic script.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Meroitic is the oldest written language in Africa, other than Egyptian, and was used from the 2nd century BC until the early 5th century AD.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The cult of the goddess Isis, for example, became popular in the Roman Empire, as obelisks and other relics were transported back to Rome.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] The Romans also imported building materials from Egypt to erect Egyptian-style structures.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Early historians such as Herodotus, Strabo, and Diodorus Siculus studied and wrote about the land, which Romans came to view as a place of mystery.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] During the Middle Ages and the Renaissance, Egyptian pagan culture was in decline after the rise of Christianity and later Islam, but interest in Egyptian antiquity continued in the writings of medieval scholars such as Dhul-Nun al-Misri and al-Maqrizi.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, European travelers and tourists brought back antiquities and wrote stories of their journeys, leading to a wave of Egyptomania across Europe, as evident in symbolism such as the Eye of Providence and the Great Seal of the United States.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] This renewed interest sent collectors to Egypt, who took, purchased, or were given many important antiquities.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Napoleon arranged the first studies in Egyptology when he brought some 150 scientists and artists to study and document Egypt's natural history, which was published in the *Description de l'Égypte*.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] In the 20th century, the Egyptian Government and archaeologists alike recognized the importance of cultural respect and integrity in excavations.
[src:adulis/ancient-egypt-p02] Since the 2010s, the Ministry of Tourism and Antiquities has overseen excavations and the recovery of artifacts.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Three centuries after the decline of Mycenaean Greece during the Bronze Age collapse, Greek urban poleis began to form in the 8th century BC, ushering in the Archaic period and the colonization of the Mediterranean Basin.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] This was followed by the age of Classical Greece, from the Greco-Persian Wars to the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC, and which included the Golden Age of Athens and the Peloponnesian War between Athens and Sparta.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The unification of Greece by Macedon under Philip II and subsequent conquest of the Achaemenid Empire by Alexander the Great spread Hellenistic civilization across the Middle East.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period is considered to have ended in 30 BC, when the last Hellenistic kingdom, Ptolemaic Egypt, was annexed by the Roman Republic.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Classical Greek culture, especially philosophy, had a powerful influence on ancient Rome, which carried a version of it throughout the Mediterranean and much of Europe.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] For this reason, Classical Greece is generally considered the cradle of Western civilization, the seminal culture from which the modern West derives many of its founding archetypes and ideas in politics, philosophy, science, and art.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in the Mediterranean region is commonly considered to have begun in the 8th century BC (around the time of the earliest recorded poetry of Homer) and ended in the 6th century AD.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in Greece was preceded by the Greek Dark Ages (c.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] 800 BC), archaeologically characterised by the protogeometric and geometric styles of designs on pottery.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Following the Dark Ages was the Archaic period, beginning around the 8th century BC, which saw early developments in Greek culture and society leading to the Classical period from the Persian invasion of Greece in 480 BC until the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Classical period is characterized by a "classical" style, i.e. one which was considered exemplary by later observers, most famously in the Parthenon of Athens.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Politically, the Classical period was dominated by Athens and the Delian League during the 5th century, but displaced by Spartan hegemony during the early 4th century BC, before power shifted to Thebes and the Boeotian League and finally to the League of Corinth led by Macedon.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] This period was shaped by the Greco-Persian Wars, the Peloponnesian War, and the Rise of Macedon.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Following the Classical period was the Hellenistic period (323–146 BC), during which Greek culture and power expanded into the Near East from the death of Alexander until the Roman conquest.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Roman Greece is usually counted from the Roman victory over the Corinthians at the Battle of Corinth in 146 BC to the establishment of Byzantium by Constantine as the capital of the Roman Empire in 330 AD.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Finally, Late Antiquity refers to the period of Christianization during the later 4th to early 6th centuries AD, consummated by the closure of the Academy of Athens by Justinian I in 529.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The historical period of ancient Greece is unique in world history as the first period attested directly in comprehensive, narrative historiography, while earlier ancient history or protohistory is known from much more fragmentary documents such as annals, king lists, and pragmatic epigraphy.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Herodotus is widely known as the "father of history": his *Histories* are eponymous of the entire field.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Written between the 450s and 420s BC, Herodotus' work reaches about a century into the past, discussing 6th-century BC historical figures such as Darius I of Persia, Cambyses II and Psamtik III, and alluding to some 8th-century BC persons such as Candaules.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The accuracy of Herodotus' works is debated.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Herodotus was succeeded by authors such as Thucydides, Xenophon, Demosthenes, Plato and Aristotle.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Most were either Athenian or pro-Athenian, which is why far more is known about the history and politics of Athens than of many other cities.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Their scope is further limited by a focus on political, military and diplomatic history, ignoring economic and social history.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The archaic period, lasting approximately from 800 to 500 BC, saw the culmination of political and social developments which had begun in the Greek Dark Age, with the *polis* (city-state) becoming the most important unit of political organisation in Greece.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The absence of powerful states in Greece after the collapse of Mycenaean power, and the geography of Greece, where many settlements were separated from their neighbours by mountainous terrain, encouraged the development of small independent city-states.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Several Greek states saw tyrants rise to power in this period, most famously at Corinth from 657 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The period also saw the founding of Greek colonies around the Mediterranean, with Euboean settlements at Al-Mina in the east as early as 800 BC, and Ischia in the west by 775.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Increasing contact with non-Greek peoples in this period, especially in the Near East, inspired developments in art and architecture, the adoption of coinage, and the development of the Greek alphabet.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Athens developed its democratic system over the course of the archaic period.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Already in the 7th century, the right of all citizen men to attend the assembly appears to have been established.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] After a failed coup led by Cylon of Athens around 636 BC, Draco was appointed to establish a code of laws in 621.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] This failed to reduce the political tension between the poor and the elites, and in 594 Solon was given the authority to enact another set of reforms, which attempted to balance the power of the rich and the poor.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the middle of the 6th century, Pisistratus established himself as a tyrant, and after his death in 527 his son Hippias inherited his position; by the end of the 6th century he had been overthrown, and Cleisthenes carried out further democratising reforms.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In Sparta, a political system with two kings, a council of elders, and five ephors developed over the course of the 8th and 7th centuries.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] According to Spartan tradition, this constitution was established by the legendary lawgiver Lycurgus.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Over the course of the First Messenian War and Second Messenian War, Sparta subjugated the neighbouring region of Messenia, enserfing the population.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the 6th century, Greek city-states began to develop formal relationships with one another, where previously individual rulers had relied on personal relationships with the elites of other cities.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Towards the end of the Archaic period, Sparta began to build a series of alliances, the Peloponnesian League, with cities including Corinth, Elis, and Megara, isolating Messenia and reinforcing Sparta's position against Argos, the other major power in the Peloponnese.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Other alliances in the 6th century included those between Elis and Heraea in the Peloponnese; and between the Greek colony Sybaris in southern Italy, its allies, and the Serdaioi.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In 499 BC, the Ionian city-states under Persian rule rebelled against their Persian-supported tyrant rulers.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Supported by troops sent from Athens and Eretria, they advanced as far as Sardis and burnt the city before being driven back by a Persian counterattack.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The revolt continued until 494, when the rebelling Ionians were defeated.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Darius did not forget that Athens had assisted the Ionian revolt, and in 490 he assembled an armada to retaliate.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Though heavily outnumbered, the Athenians—supported by their Plataean allies—defeated the Persian hordes at the Battle of Marathon, and the Persian fleet turned tail.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Ten years later, a second invasion was launched by Darius' son Xerxes.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The city-states of northern and central Greece submitted to the Persian forces without resistance, but a coalition of 31 Greek city-states, including Athens and Sparta, determined to resist the Persian invaders.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] At the same time, Greek Sicily was invaded by a Carthaginian force.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Persians were decisively defeated at sea by a primarily Athenian naval force at the Battle of Salamis, and on land in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The alliance against Persia continued, initially led by the Spartan Pausanias but from 477 by Athens, and by 460 Persia had been driven out of the Aegean.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] During this long campaign, the Delian League gradually transformed from a defensive alliance of Greek states into an Athenian empire, as Athens' growing naval power intimidated the other league states.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Athens ended its campaigns against Persia in 450, after a disastrous defeat in Egypt in 454, and the death of Cimon in action against the Persians on Cyprus in 450.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] As the Athenian fight against the Persian empire waned, conflict grew between Athens and Sparta.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Suspicious of the increasing Athenian power funded by the Delian League, Sparta offered aid to reluctant members of the League to rebel against Athenian domination.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] These tensions were exacerbated in 462 BC when Athens sent a force to aid Sparta in overcoming a helot revolt, but this aid was rejected by the Spartans.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the 450s, Athens took control of Boeotia, and won victories over Aegina and Corinth.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] However, Athens failed to win a decisive victory, and in 447 lost Boeotia again.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Athens and Sparta signed the Thirty Years' Peace in the winter of 446/445, ending the conflict.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Despite the treaty, Athenian relations with Sparta declined again in the 430s, and in 431 BC the Peloponnesian War began.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The first phase of the war saw a series of fruitless annual invasions of Attica by Sparta, while Athens successfully fought the Corinthian empire in northwest Greece and defended its own empire, despite a plague which killed the leading Athenian statesman Pericles.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The war turned after Athenian victories led by Cleon at Pylos and Sphakteria, and Sparta sued for peace, but the Athenians rejected the proposal.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Athenian failure to regain control of Boeotia at Delium and Brasidas' successes in northern Greece in 424 improved Sparta's position after Sphakteria.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] After the deaths of Cleon and Brasidas, the strongest proponents of war on each side, a peace treaty was negotiated in 421 by the Athenian general Nicias.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In 418 BC allied forces of Athens and Argos were defeated by Sparta at Mantinea.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In 415 Athens launched an ambitious naval expedition to dominate Sicily; the expedition ended in disaster at the harbor of Syracuse, with almost the entire army killed, and the ships destroyed.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Soon after the Athenian defeat in Syracuse, Athens' Ionian allies began to rebel against the Delian league, while Persia began to once again involve itself in Greek affairs on the Spartan side.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Initially the Athenian position continued relatively strong, with important victories at Cyzicus in 410 and Arginusae in 406.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] However, in 405 the Spartan Lysander defeated Athens in the Battle of Aegospotami, and began to blockade Athens' harbour; driven by hunger, Athens sued for peace, agreeing to surrender their fleet and join the Spartan-led Peloponnesian League.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Following the Athenian surrender, Sparta installed an oligarchic regime, the Thirty Tyrants, in Athens, one of a number of Spartan-backed oligarchies which rose to power after the Peloponnesian war.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Spartan predominance did not last: after only a year, the Thirty had been overthrown.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The first half of the 4th century saw the major Greek states attempt to dominate the mainland; none were successful, and their resulting weakness led to a power vacuum which was eventually filled by Macedon under Philip II and then Alexander the Great.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the immediate aftermath of the Peloponnesian war, Sparta attempted to extend their own power, leading Argos, Athens, Corinth, and Thebes to join against them.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Aiming to prevent any single Greek state gaining the dominance that would allow it to challenge Persia, the Persian king initially joined the alliance against Sparta, before imposing the Peace of Antalcidas ("King's Peace") which restored Persia's control over the Anatolian Greeks.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] By 371 BC, Thebes was in the ascendancy, defeating Sparta at the Battle of Leuctra, killing the Spartan king Cleombrotus I, and invading Laconia.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Further Theban successes against Sparta in 369 led to Messenia gaining independence; Sparta never recovered from the loss of Messenia's fertile land and the helot workforce it provided.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The rising power of Thebes led Sparta and Athens to join forces; in 362 they were defeated by Thebes at the Battle of Mantinea.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the aftermath of Mantinea, none of the major Greek states were able to dominate.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Though Thebes had won the battle, their general Epaminondas was killed, and they spent the following decades embroiled in wars with their neighbours; Athens, meanwhile, saw its second naval alliance, formed in 377, collapse in the mid-350s.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The power vacuum in Greece after the Battle of Mantinea was filled by Macedon, under Philip II, starting from the battle of Crocus field.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In 338 BC, he defeated a Greek alliance at the Battle of Chaeronea, and subsequently formed the League of Corinth.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Philip planned to lead the League to invade Persia, but was murdered in 336 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] His son Alexander the Great was left to fulfill his father's ambitions.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] After campaigns against Macedon's western and northern enemies, and those Greek states that had broken from the League of Corinth following the death of Philip, Alexander began his campaign against Persia in 334 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] He conquered Persia, defeating Darius III at the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, and after the Battle of Gaugamela in 331 BC proclaimed himself king of Asia.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] From 329 BC he led expeditions to Bactria and then India; further plans to invade Arabia and North Africa were halted by his death in 323 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The period from the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC until the death of Cleopatra, the last Macedonian ruler of Egypt, is known as the Hellenistic period.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the early part of this period, a new form of kingship developed based on Macedonian and Near Eastern traditions.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The first Hellenistic kings were previously Alexander's generals, and took power in the period following his death, though they were not part of existing royal lineages and lacked historic claims to the territories they controlled.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the early part of the Hellenistic period, the exact borders of the Hellenistic kingdoms were not settled.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Antigonus attempted to expand his territory by attacking the other successor kingdoms until they joined against him, and he was killed at the Battle of Ipsus in 301 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] His son Demetrius spent many years in Seleucid captivity, and his son, Antigonus II, only reclaimed the Macedonian throne around 276.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Meanwhile, the Seleucid kingdom gave up territory in the east to the Indian king Chandragupta Maurya in exchange for war elephants, and later lost large parts of Persia to the Parthian Empire.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] By the mid-3rd century, the kingdoms of Alexander's successors was mostly stable, though there continued to be disputes over border areas.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The great capitals of Hellenistic culture were Alexandria in the Ptolemaic Kingdom and Antioch in the Seleucid Empire.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The conquests of Alexander had numerous consequences for the Greek city-states.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] It greatly widened the horizons of the Greeks and led to a steady emigration of the young and ambitious to the new Greek empires in the east.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Many Greeks migrated to Alexandria, Antioch and the many other new Hellenistic cities founded in Alexander's wake, as far away as present-day Afghanistan and Pakistan, where the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom and the Indo-Greek Kingdom survived until the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Some city-states within Greece formed themselves into two major leagues; the Achaean League (including Corinth and Argos) and the Aetolian League.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] For much of the period until the Roman conquest, these leagues were at war, often participating in the conflicts between the Diadochi's successor states to Alexander's empire.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Antigonid Kingdom became involved in a war with the Roman Republic in the late 3rd century.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Although the First Macedonian War was inconclusive, the Romans, in typical fashion, continued to fight Macedon until it was completely absorbed into the Roman Republic (by 149 BC).
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the east, the unwieldy Seleucid Empire gradually disintegrated, although a rump survived until 64 BC, whilst the Ptolemaic Kingdom continued in Egypt until 30 BC when it too was conquered by the Romans.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Aetolian league grew wary of Roman involvement in Greece, and sided with the Seleucids in the Roman–Seleucid War; when the Romans were victorious, the league was effectively absorbed into the Republic.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Although the Achaean league outlasted both the Aetolian league and Macedon, it was also soon defeated and absorbed by the Romans in 146 BC, bringing Greek independence to an end.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Greek peninsula came under Roman rule during the 146 BC conquest of Greece after the Battle of Corinth.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Macedonia became a Roman province while southern Greece came under the surveillance of Macedonia's prefect; however, some Greek *poleis* managed to maintain a partial independence and avoid taxation.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Aegean Islands were added to this territory in 133 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Athens and other Greek cities revolted in 88 BC, and the peninsula was crushed by the Roman general Sulla.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Roman civil wars devastated the land even further, until Augustus organized the peninsula as the province of Achaea in 27 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Greece was a key eastern province of the Roman Empire, as the Roman culture had long been in fact Greco-Roman.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Greek language served as a *lingua franca* in the East and in Italy, and many Greek intellectuals such as Galen would perform most of their work in Rome.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The territory of Greece is mountainous, and as a result, ancient Greece consisted of many smaller regions, each with its own dialect, cultural peculiarities, and identity.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Regionalism and regional conflicts were prominent features of ancient Greece.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Cities tended to be located in valleys between mountains, or on coastal plains, and dominated a certain area around them.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the south lay the Peloponnese, consisting of the regions of Laconia (southeast), Messenia (southwest), Elis (west), Achaia (north), Korinthia (northeast), Argolis (east), and Arcadia (center).
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] These names survive to the present day as regional units of modern Greece, though with somewhat different boundaries.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Mainland Greece to the north, nowadays known as Central Greece, consisted of Aetolia and Acarnania in the west, Locris, Doris, and Phocis in the center, while in the east lay Boeotia, Attica, and Megaris.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Northeast lay Thessaly, while Epirus lay to the northwest.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Epirus stretched from the Ambracian Gulf in the south to the Ceraunian Mountains and the Aoos river in the north, and consisted of Chaonia (north), Molossia (center), and Thesprotia (south).
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the northeast corner was Macedonia, originally consisting Lower Macedonia and its regions, such as Emathia (Macedonia), Pieria, and Bottiaea, and later Almopia, Amphaxitis.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The original capital of Macedon was Aigai and then moved to Pella in the 4th century BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] To the north of Macedonia lay various non-Greek peoples such as the Paeonians due north, the Thracians to the northeast, and the Illyrians, with whom the Macedonians were frequently in conflict, to the northwest.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Chalcidice was settled early on by southern Greek colonists and was considered part of the Greek world, while from the late 2nd millennium BC substantial Greek settlement also occurred on the eastern shores of the Aegean, in Anatolia.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] This was not simply for trade, but also to found settlements.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] These Greek colonies were not, as Roman colonies were, dependent on their mother-city, but were independent city-states in their own right.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Greeks settled outside of Greece in two distinct ways.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The first was in permanent settlements founded by Greeks, which formed as independent poleis.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The second form was in what historians refer to as *emporia*; trading posts which were occupied by both Greeks and non-Greeks and which were primarily concerned with the manufacture and sale of goods.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Examples of this latter type of settlement are found at Al Mina in the east and Pithekoussai in the west.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] From around 750 to 500 BC, Greeks settled colonies in all directions.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] To the east, the Aegean coast of Asia Minor was colonized first, followed by Cyprus and the coasts of Thrace, the Sea of Marmara and the south coast of the Black Sea.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Eventually, Greek colonization reached as far northeast as present-day Ukraine and Russia (Taganrog).
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] To the west the coasts of Illyria, Southern Italy (called "Magna Graecia") were settled, followed by Southern France, Corsica, and even eastern Spain.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Greek colonies were also founded in Egypt and Libya.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Modern Syracuse, Naples, Marseille and Istanbul had their beginnings as the Greek colonies Syracusae (Συράκουσαι), Neapolis (Νεάπολις), Massalia (Μασσαλία) and Byzantion (Βυζάντιον).
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] These colonies played an important role in the spread of Greek influence throughout Europe and also aided in the establishment of long-distance trading networks between the Greek city-states, boosting the economy of ancient Greece.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Ancient Greece consisted of several hundred relatively independent city-states (*poleis*).
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] This was a situation unlike that in most other contemporary societies, which were either tribal or kingdoms ruling over relatively large territories.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Undoubtedly, the geography of Greece—divided and sub-divided by hills, mountains, and rivers—contributed to the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] On the one hand, the ancient Greeks had no doubt that they were "one people"; they had the same religion, same basic culture, and same language.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Furthermore, the Greeks were very aware of their tribal origins; Herodotus was able to extensively categorise the city-states by tribe.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Yet, although these higher-level relationships existed, they seem to have rarely had a major role in Greek politics.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The independence of the *poleis* was fiercely defended; unification was something rarely contemplated by the ancient Greeks.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Even when, during the second Persian invasion of Greece, a group of city-states allied themselves to defend Greece, the vast majority of *poleis* remained neutral, and after the Persian defeat, the allies quickly returned to infighting.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Thus, the major peculiarities of the ancient Greek political system were its fragmented nature (and that this does not particularly seem to have tribal origin), and the particular focus on urban centers within otherwise tiny states.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The peculiarities of the Greek system are further evidenced by the colonies that they set up throughout the Mediterranean, which, though they might count a certain Greek *polis* as their 'mother' (and remain sympathetic to her), were completely independent of the founding city.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Inevitably smaller *poleis* might be dominated by larger neighbors, but conquest or direct rule by another city-state appears to have been quite rare.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Instead the *poleis* grouped themselves into leagues, membership of which was in a constant state of flux.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Later in the Classical period, the leagues would become fewer and larger, be dominated by one city (particularly Athens, Sparta and Thebes); and often *poleis* would be compelled to join under threat of war (or as part of a peace treaty).
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Even after Philip II of Macedon conquered the heartlands of ancient Greece, he did not attempt to annex the territory or unify it into a new province, but compelled most of the *poleis* to join his own Corinthian League.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Initially many Greek city-states seem to have been petty kingdoms; there was often a city official carrying some residual, ceremonial functions of the king (*basileus*), e.g., the *archon basileus* in Athens.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] However, by the Archaic period and the first historical consciousness, most had already become aristocratic oligarchies.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] It is unclear exactly how this change occurred.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] For instance, in Athens, the kingship had been reduced to a hereditary, lifelong chief magistracy (*archon*) by c.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] 1050 BC; by 753 BC this had become a decennial, elected archonship, and finally an annually elected archonship by 683 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Through each stage, more power would have been transferred to the aristocracy as a whole, and away from a single individual.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Inevitably, the domination of politics and concomitant aggregation of wealth by small groups of families was apt to cause social unrest in many *poleis*.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In many cities a tyrant (not in the modern sense of repressive autocracies), would at some point seize control and govern according to their own will; often a populist agenda would help sustain them in power.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In a system wracked with class conflict, government by a 'strongman' was often the best solution.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Athens fell under a tyranny in the second half of the 6th century BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] When this tyranny was ended, the Athenians founded the world's first democracy as a radical solution to prevent the aristocracy regaining power.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] A citizens' assembly (the *Ecclesia*), for the discussion of city policy, had existed since the reforms of Draco in 621 BC; all citizens were permitted to attend after the reforms of Solon (early 6th century), but the poorest citizens could not address the assembly or run for office.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] With the establishment of the democracy, the assembly became the *de jure* mechanism of government; all citizens had equal privileges in the assembly.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] However, non-citizens, such as metics (foreigners living in Athens) or slaves, had no political rights at all.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] After the rise of democracy in Athens, other city-states founded democracies.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] However, many retained more traditional forms of government.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] As so often in other matters, Sparta was a notable exception to the rest of Greece, ruled through the whole period by not one, but two hereditary monarchs.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Kings of Sparta belonged to the Agiads and the Eurypontids, descendants respectively of Eurysthenes and Procles.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Both dynasties' founders were believed to be twin sons of Aristodemus, a Heraclid ruler.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] However, the powers of these kings were held in check by both a council of elders (the *Gerousia*) and magistrates specifically appointed to watch over the kings (the *Ephors*).
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Only free, land-owning, native-born men could be citizens entitled to the full protection of the law in a city-state.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In most city-states, unlike the situation in Rome, social prominence did not allow special rights.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Sometimes families controlled public religious functions, but this ordinarily did not give any extra power in the government.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In Athens, the population was divided into four social classes based on wealth.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] People could change classes if they made more money.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In Sparta, all male citizens were called *homoioi*, meaning "peers".
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] However, Spartan kings, who served as the city-state's dual military and religious leaders, came from two families.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Women in Ancient Greece appear to have primarily performed domestic tasks, managed households, and borne and reared children.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Slaves had the right to have a family and own property, subject to their master's goodwill and permission, but they had no political rights.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] By 600 BC, chattel slavery had spread in Greece.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] By the 5th century BC, slaves made up one-third of the total population in some city-states.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Between 40 and 80% of the population of Classical Athens were slaves.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Slaves outside of Sparta almost never revolted because they were made up of too many nationalities and were too scattered to organize.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] However, unlike later Western culture, the ancient Greeks did not think in terms of race.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Most families owned slaves as household servants and laborers, and even poor families might have owned a few slaves.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Owners were not allowed to beat or kill their slaves.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Owners often promised to free slaves in the future to encourage slaves to work hard.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Unlike in Rome, freedmen did not become citizens.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Instead, they were mixed into the population of *metics*, which included people from foreign countries or other city-states who were officially allowed to live in the state.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] These public slaves had a larger measure of independence than slaves owned by families, living on their own and performing specialized tasks.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In Athens, public slaves were trained to look out for counterfeit coinage, while temple slaves acted as servants of the temple's deity and Scythian slaves were employed in Athens as a police force corralling citizens to political functions.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Sparta had a special type of slaves called *helots*.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Helots were Messenians enslaved en masse during the Messenian Wars by the state and assigned to families where they were forced to stay.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Helots raised food and did household chores so that women could concentrate on raising strong children while men could devote their time to training as hoplites.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Their masters treated them harshly, and helots revolted against their masters several times.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In 370/369 BC, as a result of Epaminondas' liberation of Messenia from Spartan rule, the helot system there came to an end and the helots won their freedom.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] However, it persisted in Laconia until the 2nd century BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] For most of Greek history, education was private, except in Sparta.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] During the Hellenistic period, some city-states established public schools.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Only wealthy families could afford a teacher.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Boys learned how to read, write and quote literature.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] They also learned to sing and play one musical instrument and were trained as athletes for military service.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] They studied not for a job but to become an effective citizen.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Girls also learned to read, write and do simple arithmetic so they could manage the household.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] They almost never received education after childhood.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Boys went to school at the age of seven, or went to the barracks, if they lived in Sparta.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The three types of teachings were: grammatistes for arithmetic, kitharistes for music and dancing, and Paedotribae for sports.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Boys from wealthy families attending the private school lessons were taken care of by a *paidagogos*, a household slave selected for this task who accompanied the boy during the day.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Classes were held in teachers' private houses and included reading, writing, mathematics, singing, and playing the lyre and flute.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] When the boy became 12 years old the schooling started to include sports such as wrestling, running, and throwing discus and javelin.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In Athens, some older youths attended academy for the finer disciplines such as culture, sciences, music, and the arts.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The schooling ended at age 18, followed by military training in the army usually for one or two years.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Some of Athens' greatest such schools included the Lyceum (the so-called Peripatetic school founded by Aristotle of Stageira) and the Platonic Academy (founded by Plato of Athens).
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The education system of the wealthy ancient Greeks is also called Paideia.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] At its economic height in the 5th and 4th centuries BC, the free citizenry of Classical Greece represented perhaps the most prosperous society in the ancient world, some economic historians considering Greece one of the most advanced pre-industrial economies.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In terms of wheat, wages reached an estimated 7–12 kg (15–26 lb) daily for an unskilled worker in urban Athens, 2–3 times the 3.75 kg (8.3 lb) of an unskilled rural labourer in Roman Egypt, though Greek farm incomes too were on average lower than those available to urban workers.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] At least in the Archaic period, the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece, with many competing city-states, increased the frequency of conflict but conversely limited the scale of warfare.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Unable to maintain professional armies, the city-states relied on their own citizens to fight.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] This inevitably reduced the potential duration of campaigns, as citizens would need to return to their own professions (especially in the case of, for example, farmers).
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Campaigns would therefore often be restricted to summer.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] When battles occurred, they were usually set piece and intended to be decisive.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Casualties were slight compared to later battles, rarely amounting to more than five percent of the losing side, but the slain often included the most prominent citizens and generals who led from the front.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The scale and scope of warfare in ancient Greece changed dramatically as a result of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] To fight the enormous armies of the Achaemenid Empire was effectively beyond the capabilities of a single city-state.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The eventual triumph of the Greeks was achieved by alliances of city-states (the exact composition changing over time), allowing the pooling of resources and division of labor.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Although alliances between city-states occurred before this time, nothing on this scale had been seen before.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The rise of Athens and Sparta as pre-eminent powers during this conflict led directly to the Peloponnesian War, which saw further development of the nature of warfare, strategy and tactics.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Fought between leagues of cities dominated by Athens and Sparta, the increased manpower and financial resources increased the scale and allowed the diversification of warfare.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Set-piece battles during the Peloponnesian war proved indecisive and instead there was increased reliance on attritionary strategies, naval battles and blockades and sieges.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] These changes greatly increased the number of casualties and the disruption of Greek society.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Athens owned one of the largest war fleets in ancient Greece.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] It had over 200 triremes each powered by 170 oarsmen who were seated in 3 rows on each side of the ship.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The city could afford such a large fleet—it had over 34,000 oarsmen—because it owned a lot of silver mines that were worked by slaves.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] According to Josiah Ober, Greek city-states faced approximately a one-in-three chance of destruction during the archaic and classical period.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek philosophy focused on the role of reason and inquiry.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In many ways, it had an important influence on modern philosophy, as well as modern science.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Clear unbroken lines of influence lead from ancient Greek and Hellenistic philosophers, to medieval Muslim philosophers and Islamic scientists, to the European Renaissance and Enlightenment, to the secular sciences of the modern day.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Neither reason nor inquiry began with the ancient Greeks.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Defining the difference between the Greek quest for knowledge and the quests of the elder civilizations, such as the ancient Egyptians and Babylonians, has long been a topic of study by theorists of civilization.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The first known philosophers of Greece were the pre-Socratics, who attempted to provide naturalistic, non-mythical descriptions of the world.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] They were followed by Socrates, one of the first philosophers based in Athens during its golden age whose ideas, despite being known by second-hand accounts instead of writings of his own, laid the basis of Western philosophy.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Socrates' disciple Plato, who wrote *The Republic* and established a radical difference between ideas and the concrete world, and Plato's disciple Aristotle, who wrote extensively about nature and ethics, are also immensely influential in Western philosophy to this day.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The later Hellenistic philosophy, also originating in Greece, is defined by names such as Antisthenes (cynicism), Zeno of Citium (stoicism) and Plotinus (Neoplatonism).
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek literature was poetry and was composed for performance rather than private consumption.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek poet known is Homer, although he was certainly part of an existing tradition of oral poetry.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Homer's poetry, though it was developed around the same time that the Greeks developed writing, would have been composed orally; the first poet to certainly compose their work in writing was Archilochus, a lyric poet from the mid-7th century BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Tragedy developed around the end of the archaic period, taking elements from across the pre-existing genres of late archaic poetry.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Like poetry, Greek prose had its origins in the archaic period, and the earliest writers of Greek philosophy, history, and medical literature all date to the 6th century BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Prose first emerged as the writing style adopted by the presocratic philosophers Anaximander and Anaximenes—though Thales of Miletus, considered the first Greek philosopher, apparently wrote nothing.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Prose as a genre reached maturity in the classical era, and the major Greek prose genres—philosophy, history, rhetoric, and dialogue—developed in this period.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period saw the literary centre of the Greek world move from Athens, where it had been in the classical period, to Alexandria.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] At the same time, other Hellenistic kings such as the Antigonids and the Attalids were patrons of scholarship and literature, turning Pella and Pergamon respectively into cultural centres.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] It was thanks to this cultural patronage by Hellenistic kings, and especially the Museum at Alexandria, that so much ancient Greek literature has survived.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Library of Alexandria, part of the Museum, had the previously unenvisaged aim of collecting together copies of all known authors in Greek.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Almost all of the surviving non-technical Hellenistic literature is poetry, and Hellenistic poetry tended to be highly intellectual, blending different genres and traditions, and avoiding linear narratives.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period also saw a shift in the ways literature was consumed—while in the archaic and classical periods literature had typically been experienced in public performance, in the Hellenistic period it was more commonly read privately.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] At the same time, Hellenistic poets began to write for private, rather than public, consumption.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] With Octavian's victory at Actium in 31 BC, Rome began to become a major centre of Greek literature, as important Greek authors such as Strabo and Dionysius of Halicarnassus came to Rome.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The period of greatest innovation in Greek literature under Rome was the "long second century" from approximately 80 AD to around 230 AD.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] This innovation was especially marked in prose, with the development of the novel and a revival of prominence for display oratory both dating to this period.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In Ancient Greek society, music was ever-present and considered a fundamental component of civilisation.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] It was an important part of public religious worship, private ceremonies such as weddings and funerals, and household entertainment.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Men sang and played music at the symposium; both men and women sang at work; and children's games involved song and dance.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek music was primarily vocal, sung either by a solo singer or a chorus, and usually accompanied by an instrument; purely instrumental music was less common.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Greeks used stringed instruments, including lyres, harps, and lutes; and wind instruments, of which the most important was the *aulos*, a reed instrument.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Percussion instruments played a relatively unimportant role supporting stringed and wind instruments, and were used in certain religious cults.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek mathematics contributed many important developments to mathematics, including the basic rules of geometry, the idea of formal mathematical proof, and discoveries in number theory, mathematical analysis, applied mathematics, and approached close to establishing integral calculus.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The discoveries of several Greek mathematicians, including Pythagoras, Euclid, and Archimedes, are still used in mathematical teaching today.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Greeks developed astronomy, which they treated as a branch of mathematics, to a highly sophisticated level.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The first geometrical, three-dimensional models to explain the apparent motion of the planets were developed in the 4th century BC by Eudoxus of Cnidus and Callippus of Cyzicus.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Their younger contemporary Heraclides Ponticus proposed that the Earth rotates around its axis.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the 3rd century BC, Aristarchus of Samos was the first to suggest a heliocentric system.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Archimedes in his treatise The Sand Reckoner revives Aristarchus' hypothesis that *"the fixed stars and the Sun remain unmoved, while the Earth revolves about the Sun on the circumference of a circle"*.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Otherwise, only fragmentary descriptions of Aristarchus' idea survive.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Eratosthenes, using the angles of shadows created at widely separated regions, estimated the circumference of the Earth with great accuracy.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the 2nd century BC Hipparchus of Nicea made a number of contributions, including the first measurement of precession and the compilation of the first star catalog in which he proposed the modern system of apparent magnitudes.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Antikythera mechanism, a device for calculating the movements of planets, dates from about 80 BC and was the first ancestor of the astronomical computer.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] It was discovered in an ancient shipwreck off the Greek island of Antikythera, between Kythera and Crete.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The device became famous for its use of a differential gear, previously believed to have been invented in the 16th century, and the miniaturization and complexity of its parts, comparable to a clock made in the 18th century.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The original mechanism is displayed in the Bronze collection of the National Archaeological Museum of Athens, accompanied by a replica.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The ancient Greeks also made important discoveries in the medical field.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Hippocrates was a physician of the Classical period, and is considered one of the most outstanding figures in the history of medicine.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] He is referred to as the "father of medicine" in recognition of his lasting contributions to the field as the founder of the Hippocratic school of medicine.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] This intellectual school revolutionized medicine in ancient Greece, establishing it as a discipline distinct from other fields that it had traditionally been associated with (notably theurgy and philosophy), thus making medicine a profession.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The art of ancient Greece has exercised an enormous influence on the culture of many countries from ancient times to the present day, particularly in the areas of sculpture and architecture.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the West, the art of the Roman Empire was largely derived from Greek models.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] In the East, Alexander the Great's conquests initiated several centuries of exchange between Greek, Central Asian and Indian cultures, resulting in Greco-Buddhist art, with ramifications as far as Japan.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Following the Renaissance in Europe, the humanist aesthetic and the high technical standards of Greek art inspired generations of European artists.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Well into the 19th century, the classical tradition derived from Greece dominated the art of the Western world.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Religion was a central part of ancient Greek life.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Though the Greeks of different cities and tribes worshipped similar gods, religious practices were not uniform and the gods were thought of differently in different places.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The Greeks were polytheistic, worshipping many gods, but as early as the 6th century BC a pantheon of twelve Olympians began to develop.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Greek religion was influenced by the practices of the Greeks' near eastern neighbours at least as early as the archaic period, and by the Hellenistic period this influence was seen in both directions.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The most important religious act in ancient Greece was animal sacrifice, most commonly of sheep and goats.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Sacrifice was accompanied by public prayer, and prayer and hymns were themselves a major part of ancient Greek religious life.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] The civilization of ancient Greece has been immensely influential on language, politics, educational systems, philosophy, science, and the arts.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] It became the *Leitkultur* of the Roman Empire to the point of marginalizing native Italic traditions.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] Via the Roman Empire, Greek culture came to be foundational to Western culture in general.
[src:adulis/ancient-greece] A modern revival of Classical Greek learning took place in the Neoclassicism movement in 18th- and 19th-century Europe and the Americas.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] There are also several historical forms.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:adulis/ancient-greek-language] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Well-known ancient artwork and sculptures, each representing a certain civilisation.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] The three-age system periodises ancient history into the Stone Age, the Bronze Age, and the Iron Age, with recorded history usually considered to begin with the Bronze Age.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] The start and end of the three ages vary between world regions.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] In many regions the Bronze Age is generally considered to begin a few centuries prior to 3000 BC, while the end of the Iron Age varies from the early first millennium BC in some regions to the late first millennium AD in others.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] During the time period of ancient history, the world population was exponentially increasing due to the Neolithic Revolution, which was in full progress.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] In 10,000 BC, the world population stood at an estimated 2 million, it rose to 45 million by 3000 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] By the Iron Age in 1000 BC, the population had risen to 72 million.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] By the end of the ancient period in AD 500, the world population is thought to have stood at 209 million.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] In 10,500 years, the world population increased by 100 times.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Prehistory is the period before written history.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Most of the knowledge of that period comes from the work of archaeologists.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] The early human migrations in the Lower Paleolithic saw *Homo erectus* spread across Eurasia 1.8 million years ago.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Evidence for the use of fire has been dated as early as 1.8 million years ago, a date which is contested, with generally accepted evidence for the controlled use of fire dating to 780,000 years ago.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Actual use of hearths first appears 400,000 years ago.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Dates for the emergence of *Homo sapiens* (modern humans) range from 250,000 to 160,000 years ago, with the varying dates being based on DNA studies and fossils respectively.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Some 50,000 years ago, *Homo sapiens* migrated out of Africa.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] They reached Australia about 45,000 years ago, southwestern Europe about the same time, southeastern Europe and Siberia around 40,000 years ago, and Japan about 30,000 years ago.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Humans migrated to the Americas about 15,000 years ago.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Evidence for agriculture emerges in about 9000 BC in what is now eastern Turkey and spread through the Fertile Crescent.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Settlement at Göbekli Tepe began around 9500 BC and may have the world's oldest temple.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] The Nile River Valley has evidence of sorghum and millet cultivation starting around 8000 BC and agricultural use of yams in Western Africa perhaps dates to the same time period.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Cultivation of millet, rice, and legumes began around 7000 BC in China.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Taro cultivation in New Guinea dates to about 7000 BC also with squash cultivation in Mesoamerica perhaps sharing that date.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Animal domestication began with the domestication of dogs, which dates to at least 15,000 years ago, and perhaps even earlier.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Sheep and goats were domesticated around 9000 BC in the Fertile Crescent, alongside the first evidence for agriculture.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Other animals, such as pigs and poultry, were later domesticated and used as food sources.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Cattle and water buffalo were domesticated around 7000 BC and horses, donkeys, and camels were domesticated by about 4000 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] All of these animals were used not only for food, but to carry and pull people and loads, greatly increasing human ability to do work.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] The invention of the simple plough by 6000 BC further increased agricultural efficiency.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Metal use in the form of hammered copper items predates the discovery of smelting of copper ores, which happened around 6000 BC in western Asia and independently in eastern Asia before 2000 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Gold and silver use dates to between 6000 and 5000 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Alloy metallurgy began with bronze in about 3500 BC in Mesopotamia and was developed independently in China by 2000 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Pottery developed independently throughout the world, with fired pots appearing first among the Jomon of Japan and in West Africa at Mali.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Sometime between 5000 and 4000 BC the potter's wheel was invented.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] By 3000 BC, the pottery wheel was adapted into wheeled vehicles which could be used to carry loads further and easier than with human or animal power alone.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Writing developed separately in five different locations in human history: Mesopotamia, Egypt, India, China, and Mesoamerica.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] By 3400 BC, "proto-literate" cuneiform spread in the Middle East.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Egypt developed its own system of hieroglyphs by about 3200 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] By 2800 BC the Indus Valley Civilisation had developed its Indus script, which remains undeciphered.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Chinese Characters were independently developed in China during the Shang dynasty in the form of the Oracle Bone Script dating to the period 1600 to 1100 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p01] Writing in Mesoamerica dates to 600 BC with the Zapotec civilization.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The ancient Near East is considered the cradle of civilisation.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] It began the study of the stars and the sciences of astronomy and mathematics.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Mesopotamia is the site of some of the earliest known civilisations in the world.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Agricultural communities emerged in the area with the Halaf culture around 8000 BC and continued to expand through the Ubaid period around 6000 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Cities began in the Uruk period (4000–3100 BC) and expanded during the Jemdet Nasr (3100–2900 BC) and Early Dynastic (2900–2350 BC) periods.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The surplus of storable foodstuffs created by this economy allowed the population to settle in one place instead of migrating after crops and herds.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] It also allowed for a much greater population density, and in turn required an extensive labour force and division of labour.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] This organisation led to the necessity of record keeping and the development of writing.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Babylonia was an Amorite state in lower Mesopotamia (modern southern Iraq), with Babylon as its capital.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Babylonia emerged when Hammurabi created an empire out of the territories of the former kingdoms of Sumer and Akkad.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Neo-Babylonian Empire, or Chaldea, was Babylonia from the 7th and 6th centuries BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Under the reign of Nebuchadnezzar II, it conquered Jerusalem.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] This empire also created the Hanging Gardens of Babylon and the still-surviving Ishtar Gate as architectural embellishments of its capital at Babylon.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Akkad was a city and its surrounding region near Babylon.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Akkad also became the capital of the Akkadian Empire.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Despite an extensive search, the precise site has never been found.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Akkad reached the height of its power between about 2330 and 2150 BC, following the conquests of King Sargon of Akkad.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Through the spread of Sargon's empire, the language of Akkad, known as Akkadian from the city, spread and replaced the Sumerian language in Mesopotamia and eventually by 1450 BC was the main language of diplomacy in the Near East.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Assyria was originally a region on the Upper Tigris, where a small state was created in the 19th century BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The capital was at Assur, which gave the state its name.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Later, as a nation and empire that came to control all of the Fertile Crescent, Egypt, and much of Anatolia, the term "Assyria proper" referred to roughly the northern half of Mesopotamia (the southern half being Babylonia), with Nineveh as its capital.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Assyrian kings controlled a large kingdom at three different times in history.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] These are called the *Old* (20th to 18th centuries BC), *Middle* (14th to 11th centuries BC), and *Neo-Assyrian* (9th to 7th centuries BC) kingdoms, or periods.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Mitanni was a Hurrian empire in northern Mesopotamia founded around 1500 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Mitanians conquered and controlled Assyria until the 14th century BC while contending with Egypt for control of parts of modern Syria.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Its capital was Washukanni, whose precise location has not been determined by archaeologists.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Medes and Persians were peoples who had appeared in the Iranian plateau around 1500 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Both peoples spoke Indo-European languages and were mostly pastoralists with a tradition of horse archery.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Medes established their own Median Empire by the 6th century BC, having defeated the Neo-Assyrian Empire with the Chaldeans in 614 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Achaemenid Empire was founded by Cyrus the Great, who first became king of the Persians, then conquered the Medes, Lydia, and Babylon by 539 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The empire built on earlier Mesopotamian systems of government to govern their large empire.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] By building roads, they improved both the ability to send governmental instructions throughout their lands as well as improving the ability of their military forces to be deployed rapidly.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Increased trade and upgraded farming techniques increased wealth, but also exacerbated inequalities between social classes.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The empire's location at the centre of trading networks spread its intellectual and philosophical ideas throughout a wide area, and its religion, while not itself spreading far, had an impact on later religions such as Christianity, Islam, and Judaism.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Cyrus' son Cambyses II conquered Egypt, while a later emperor, Darius the Great, expanded the empire to the Indus River, creating the largest empire in the world to that date.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] But Darius and his son Xerxes I failed to expand into Greece, with expeditions in 490 and 480 BC eventually failing.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Achaemenid dynasty and empire fell to Alexander the Great by 330 BC, and after Alexander's death, much of the area previously ruled by the Cyrus and his successors was ruled by the Seleucid dynasty.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Parthia was an Iranian civilisation situated in the northeastern part of modern Iran.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Their power was based on a combination of military power based on heavy cavalry with a decentralised governing structure based on a federated system.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Parthian Empire was led by the Arsacid dynasty, which by around 155 BC under Mithradates I had mostly conquered the Seleucid Empire.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Parthia had many wars with the Romans, but it was rebellions within the empire that ended it in the 3rd century AD.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Sasanian Empire began when the Parthian Empire ended in AD 224.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Their rulers claimed the Achaemenids as ancestors and set up their capital at Ctesiphon in Mesopotamia.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Their period of greatest military expansion occurred under Shapur I, who by the time of his death in AD 272 had defeated Roman imperial armies and set up buffer states between the Sasanians and Roman Empires.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] After Shapur, the Sasanians were under more pressure from the Kushans to their east as well as the Roman then Byzantine Empire to its west.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] However, the Sasanians rebuilt and founded numerous cities and their merchants travelled widely and introduced crops such as sugar, rice, and cotton into the Iranian plateau.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] But in AD 651, the last Sassanid emperor was killed by the expanding Islamic Arabs.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Hittites first came to Anatolia about 1900 BC and during the period 1600–1500 they expanded into Mesopotamia where they adopted the cuneiform script to their Indo-European language.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] By 1200 their empire stretched to Phoenicia and eastern Anatolia.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] They improved two earlier technologies from Mesopotamia and spread these new techniques widely – improved iron working and light chariots with spoked wheels in warfare.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Hittites introduced the casting of iron with molds and then hammering it which enabled weapons and tools to be made stronger and also cheaper.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Although chariots had been used previously, the use of spoked wheels allowed the chariots to be much lighter and more maneuverable.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] In 1274 BC the Hittites clashed with the Egyptians at the Battle of Kadesh, where both sides claimed victory.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] In 1207 BC the Hittite capital of Hattusa was sacked, ending the Hittite Empire.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Israel and Judah were related Iron Age kingdoms of the ancient Levant and had existed during the Iron Ages and the Neo-Babylonian, Persian and Hellenistic periods.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The name Israel first appears in the stele of the Egyptian pharaoh Merneptah around 1209 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] This "Israel" was a cultural and probably political entity of the central highlands, well enough established to be perceived by the Egyptians as a possible challenge to their hegemony, but an ethnic group rather than an organised state.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Israel had emerged by the middle of the 9th century BC, when the Assyrian King Shalmaneser III named "Ahab the Israelite" among his enemies at the battle of Qarqar (853).
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Judah emerged somewhat later than Israel, probably during the 9th century BC, but the subject is one of considerable controversy.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Israel came into conflict with the Assyrians, who conquered Israel in 722 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Neo-Babylonian Empire did the same to Judah in 586.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] After both conquests, the conquering forces deported many of the inhabitants to other regions of their respective empires.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Phoenicia was an ancient civilisation centred in the north of ancient Canaan, with its heartland along the coastal regions of modern-day Lebanon, Syria and Israel.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Phoenician civilisation was an enterprising maritime trading culture that spread across the Mediterranean between the period of 1550 to 300 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] One Phoenician colony, Carthage, ruled an empire in the Western Mediterranean until being defeated by Rome in the Punic Wars.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Phoenicians invented the Phoenician alphabet, the forerunner of the modern alphabet still in use today.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The history of Pre-Islamic Arabia before the rise of Islam in the AD 630s is not known in great detail.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Archaeological exploration in the Arabian Peninsula has been sparse; indigenous written sources are limited to the many inscriptions and coins from southern Arabia.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Existing material consists primarily of written sources from other traditions (such as Egyptians, Greeks, Persians, Romans, etc.) and oral traditions later recorded by Islamic scholars.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] A number of small kingdoms existed in Arabia from around AD 100 to perhaps about AD 400.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Ancient Egypt was a long-lived civilisation geographically located in north-eastern Africa.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] It was concentrated along the middle to lower reaches of the Nile River, reaching its greatest extent during the 2nd millennium BC, which is referred to as the New Kingdom period.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] It reached broadly from the Nile Delta in the north, as far south as Jebel Barkal at the Fourth Cataract of the Nile.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Extensions to the geographical range of ancient Egyptian civilisation included, at different times, areas of the southern Levant, the Eastern Desert and the Red Sea coastline, the Sinai Peninsula, and the Western Desert (focused on the several oases).
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Ancient Egypt developed over at least three and a half millennia.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] It began with the incipient unification of Nile Valley polities around 3100 BC, traditionally under Menes.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Overseeing these activities were a socio-political and economic elite under the figure of a (semi)-divine ruler from a succession of ruling dynasties.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Ancient Egyptian history is divided across various periods, beginning with the Old Kingdom, which saw pyramid building on a large scale.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] After 2100 BC, the Old Kingdom dissolved into smaller states during the First Intermediate Period, which lasted about 100 years.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Middle Kingdom began around 2000 BC with the reunification of Egypt under pharoes ruling from Thebes.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Middle Kingdom ended with the conquest of northern Egypt by the Hyksos around 1650 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Hyksos were expelled from Egypt and the land was reunited in the New Kingdom around 1550 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] This period lasted until about 1000 BC, and saw Egypt expand its borders into Palestine and Syria.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Third Intermediate Period was marked by the rule of priests as well as the conquest of Egypt by Nubian kings and then later Assyria, Persia, and Macedonians.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Carthage was founded around 814 BC by Phoenician settlers.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Ancient Carthage was a city-state that ruled an empire through alliances and trade influence that stretched throughout North Africa and modern Spain.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] At the height of the city's influence, its empire included most of the western Mediterranean.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The empire was in a constant state of struggle with the Roman Republic, which led to a series of conflicts known as the Punic Wars.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] After the third and final Punic War, Carthage was destroyed and then occupied by Roman forces.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Nearly all of the territory held by Carthage fell into Roman hands.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Ta-Seti kingdom in Nubia to the south of Egypt was conquered by Egyptian rulers around 3100 BC, but by 2500 BC the Nubians had created a new kingdom further south, known as the Kingdom of Kush, centred on the upper Nile with a capital at Kerma.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] In the Egyptian New Kingdom period, Kush once more was conquered by Egypt.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] However, by 1100 BC a new kingdom of Kush had formed, with a capital at Napata.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Nubian rulers conquered Egypt around 760 BC and retained control for about a century.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Kingdom of Aksum was an important trading nation in northeastern Africa centred in present-day Eritrea and northern Ethiopia, it existed from approximately AD 100 to 940, growing from the Iron Age proto-Aksumite period around the 4th century BC to achieve prominence by the 1st century AD.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Kingdom of Aksum at its height by the early 6th-century AD extended through much of modern Ethiopia and across the Red Sea to Arabia.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The capital city of the empire was Aksum, now in northern Ethiopia.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Nok culture appeared in Nigeria around 1000 BC and mysteriously vanished around AD 200.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The civilisation's social system is thought to have been highly advanced.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Nok civilisation was considered to be the earliest sub-Saharan producer of life-sized Terracotta which have been discovered by archaeologists.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Nok also used iron smelting that may have been independently developed.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The civilisation of Djenné-Djenno was located in the Niger River Valley in the country of Mali and is considered to be among the oldest urbanised centres and the best-known archaeology site in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] This archaeological site is located about 3 kilometers (1.9 miles) away from the modern town and is believed to have been involved in long-distance trade and possibly the domestication of African rice.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The site is believed to exceed 33 hectares (82 acres); however, this is yet to be confirmed with extensive survey work.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] With the help of archaeological excavations mainly by Susan and Roderick McIntosh, the site is known to have been occupied from 250 BC to AD 900.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The city is believed to have been abandoned and moved where the current city is located due to the spread of Islam and the building of the Great Mosque of Djenné.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Previously, it was assumed that advanced trade networks and complex societies did not exist in the region until the arrival of traders from Southwest Asia.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] However, sites such as Djenné-Djenno disprove this, as these traditions in West Africa flourished long before.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Towns similar to that at Djenne-Jeno also developed at the site of Dia, also in Mali along the Niger River, from around 900 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Dhar Tichitt and Oualata were prominent among the early urban centres, dated to 2000 BC, in present-day Mauritania.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] About 500 stone settlements littered the region in the former savannah of the Sahara.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] It has been found that the Soninke of the Mandé peoples were responsible for constructing such settlements.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Around 300 BC, the region became more desiccated and the settlements began to decline, most likely relocating to Koumbi Saleh.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] From the type of architecture and pottery, it is believed that Tichit was related to the subsequent Ghana Empire.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Old Jenne (Djenne) began to be settled around 300 BC, producing iron and with sizeable population, evidenced in crowded cemeteries.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The inhabitants and creators of these settlements during these periods are thought to have been ancestors of the Soninke people.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Peoples speaking precursors to the modern-day Bantu languages began to spread throughout southern Africa, and by 2000 BC they were expanding past the Congo River and into the Great Lakes area.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] By AD 1000 these groups had spread throughout all of southern Africa south of the equator.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Iron metallurgy and agriculture spread along with these peoples, with the cultivation of millet, oil palms, sorghum, and yams as well as the use of domesticated cattle, pigs, and sheep.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] These technologies helped increase population, and settled communities became common in sub-Saharan Africa except in deserts or heavy forests.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Paleolithic tools have been discovered in India dating to 200,000 years ago, and Neolithic sites are known from near the Indus Valley dating to around 8000 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Agriculture began in the Indus Valley around 7000 BC, and reached the Ganges Valley by 3000 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Barley, cotton, and wheat were grown and the population had domesticated cattle, goats, and sheep.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The Indus Valley Civilisation developed around 3000 BC in the Indus and Ghaggar-Hakra river valleys of north-east Afghanistan, Pakistan, and western India.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Another name for this civilisation is Harappan, after the first of its cities to be excavated, Harappa (now in the Pakistani province of Punjab).
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Harappan civilisation grew out of the earlier agricultural communities as they evolved into cities.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] These communities created and traded jewelry, figurines, and seals that appear widely scattered throughout Mesopotamia, Afghanistan, and Iran.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Chickens were domesticated in addition to the earlier crops and animals.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] They developed their own writing system, the Indus Valley script, which is still mostly undeciphered.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The exact structure of society and the way the cities were governed is not known.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] By about 1600 BC, the Indus Valley culture had abandoned many of their cities, including Mohenjo-Daro.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The exact reason for this decline is not known.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Indo-European speaking peoples began to spread into India about 1500 BC.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] The *Rigveda*, in Sanskrit, dates to this period and begins a period often known as the Vedic period.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Between 1500 and 500 BC these peoples spread throughout most of India and had begun to found small cities.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Vedic society was characterised by the *varna* system which divided society into four broad castes, which were later elaborated.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] By the end of the Vedic period, this way of organising society had become central to Indian society.
[src:adulis/ancient-p02] Religion in the late Vedic period was evolving into Hinduism, which spread throughout Southeast Asia.
